es.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}} ||Colonel Robert, Viceroy, Jocelyn.{{sfn|British War Office|1797|p=34}}||18 July 1795 || || \n|-\n| ||Second Regiment <!--||-->||Colonel Edmund, Lord Glentworth.{{sfn|British War Office|1797|p=35}}||18 July 1795 || || \n|}\n\n==List of fencible infantry regiments raised between 1793 and 1803==\n\n===Scottish fencibles===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!loc-<br/>ale||Name||Uniform||Commander||Raised||Disbanded||Notes\n|-\n|SH<ref name=Key group=lower-alpha/>\n|Princess of Wales' (Aberdeen Highland) Regiment.* \n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Sir James Leith.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|25 October 1794\n|11 September 1803\n|Raised 25 October 1794. Embodied at Aberdeen. Disbanded in Ireland, 11 September 1803. \n|-\n|SL\n|Angus Volunteers\n|Facings Buff,{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}} or facings yellow, and bonnet and trews {{sfn|Reid|2011|p=20}}\n|Major-Commandant John Fraser.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|27 September 1794\n|1799\n|Strength, two companies. \n|-\n|SL\n|Angusshire Regiment\n|Facings yellow<ref group=lower-alpha>\"According to Colonel Hamilton Smith this corps wore the bonnet and kilt\" {{harv|Scobie|1914|p=355}}, but it may have been bonnet and trews {{harv|Reid|2011|p=20}}.</ref> \n|Colonel Archibald Douglas.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|20 October 1794\n|19 July 1802\n| Had a good many Highlanders from the Highland borders. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Perth. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Argyle Fencibles (1793)|1st Argyllshire Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel George, Marquis of Lorne, Afterwards George, 6th Duke of Argyll.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|2 March \n|1799\n|Embodied at Stirling. Its services were confined to Scotland.\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Argyle Fencibles (1794)|2nd Argyllshire Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings Blue \n|Colonel Henry Mord Clavering.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|25 October 1794\n|24 July 1802\n|Served in Ireland. Disbanded at [[Ayr]]. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Argyle Fencibles (1798)|3rd Argyllshire Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Archibald Macneill of Colonsay.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|15 June 1798\n|3 July 1802\n|The name of Argyll did not properly apply to this corps, as the number of Argyllshire men was very small. Its service extended to any part of Europe,<ref group=lower-alpha>The soldiers of those fencible regiments whose services extended, or who volunteered their services (and were accepted), to any part of Europe, or the world, were entitled to pensions when disabled, in the same manner as if in [[regiments of the line]]. Neither at that period nor for many years after were there any such pensions to officers, however severe their wounds, or however much disabled ({{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=355}} cites Stewart of Garth, ''Sketches of the Highlanders'', vol. ii. p. 330.).</ref>  and in 1800 was sent to Gibraltar. Ordered home at the peace of 1801. Disbanded at Dumbarton. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Breadalbane Regiment (1793)|Breadalbane Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel [[John Campbell, 1st Marquess of Breadalbane|Earl of Breadalbane]].\n|2 March 1793\n|28 July 1802\n|3 Battalions\n|-\n|\n|[[Breadalbane Regiment (1793)|Breadalbane Regiment \u2014 1st Battalion]]\n|\n|Lieutenant-Colonel William Maxwell Morrison (late [[77th Foot]]).{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=355}}\n|2 March 1793\n|18 April 1799\n|Embodied at [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]]. Volunteered for duty in Ireland, August 1798, but its services were not required. Remained in Scotland. Disbanded at Fort George.<ref group=lower-alpha>[[Duncan Ban MacIntyre]], the famous hunter-bard of Glenorchy, was a soldier in this battalion, in which he served till its disbandment. His discharge document is still in existence ({{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=355}} cites {{citation|title=The Gaelic Songs of Duncan MacIntyre |first=G. |last=Calder}}).</ref>\n|-\n|\n|[[Breadalbane Regiment (1793)|Breadalbane Regiment \u2014 2nd Battalion]]\n|\n|Lieutenant-Colonel Andrew Macdouall of Logan.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}}\n|8 March 1793\n|18 April 1799\n|Embodied at Perth. In 1798 the greater part of this corps volunteered for service in Ireland, and landed at Carrickfergus in September. Returned to Scotland in March 1799. Disbanded at Paisley. \n|-\n|\n|[[Breadalbane Regiment (1794)|Breadalbane Regiment \u2014 3rd Battalion]] \n|\n|Lieutenant-Colonel John Campbell of Achallader.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} \n|9 December 1794\n|28 July 1802\n|Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Ayr. \n|-\n|En\n|Loyal British Regiment\n|Facings Blue\n|Colonel Sir Robert Stuart, Bart.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} \n|24 October 1794\n|1802 \n| \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Caithness Legion]]. \n|The bonnet and tartan pantaloons (truis). Facings yellow.<ref group=lower-alpha>The belt-plate of this regiment bore the Thistle and Crown, with the word \"Caithness\" above, and below, the legend, \"Flodden Field\" {{harv|Scobie|1914|p=356}}.</ref> \n|Colonel Sir Benjamin Dunbar of Hempriggs. \n|15 November 1794\n|1802\n|Served in Ireland. Disbanded at [[Enniscorthy]]. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Clan-Alpine Fencibles|Royal Clan Alpine Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings Blue. \n|Colonel Alex. Macgregor Murray of Napier Rusky.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}}\n|21 September 1798\n|24 July 1802\n|Raised for general service in Europe. Embodied at Stirling. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Stirling. \n|-\n|??\n|{{anchor|Banffshire Fencibles}}|Duke of York's Own (Banffshire) Regiment\n|The bonnet and truis.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} Facings probably yellow.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}} \n|Colonel [[Andrew Hay (British Army officer)|Andrew Hay]] of Mountblairey.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}}\n|26 July 1798\n|1802\n|This regiment had a number of Highlanders in its ranks.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} Garrisoned Gibraltar.<ref name=Gibraltar-garrison group=lower-alpha>\"The Regiments in the Garrison were [[5th Foot|5th]], [[44th Foot|44th]], [[#Cambrian Rangers|Cambrian Rangers]], [[#Banffshire Fencibles|Banffshire Fencibles]], [[Argyle Fencibles (1794)|2nd Argllshire Fencibles]], and the [[#Prince of Wales Own Fencibles|Prince of Wales Own Fencibles]], Governor's Letter Book, 1759\u20131800, GGA.\" {{harv|Musteen|2011|p=218 (note 54)}} \u2014 other sources state it was the 3rd Argl Fencibles who garrisoned Gibraltar.</ref> \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Dumbarton Fencible Regiment]]\n|Black facings, Highland dress, {{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} or trews {{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}} \n|Colonel Colin Campbell of Stonefield.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=356}} \n|14 August 1794\n|5 October 1802\n|Embodied at Dumbarton. Served in Guernsey, and afterwards in Ireland during the rebellion, where it was actively occupied and employed as a light infantry corps in the mountains, under Sir John Moore, who kept it constantly near his person. \"By the recommendation of General Moore, a detachment of the regiment was ordered as a guard to 400 rebel prisoners sent to Prussia, with directions that 'the detachment should consist entirely of Highlanders, as the service required confidential, trustworthy men'.\".<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=356}} cites General Stewart of Garth.</ref> Disbanded at Dumbarton. \n|-\n|SL\n|[[Elgin's Regiment of Fencible Infantry|Lord Elgin's Regiment]].\n|The bonnet and truis.<ref group=lower-alpha>General Stewart and Colonel H. Smith's Mss. According to Colonel Smith's drawings, purses (sporran) were worn by regiments in truis as well as by kilted ones. The purses he shows are mere indications, all alike, and evidently not regimental variations. It seems improbable, however, that purses were worn in all the regiments wearing truis.</ref> Facings green \n|Colonel Thomas, Earl of Elgin.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=357}}\n|28 November 1794\n|15 October 1802\n|There were about 300 Highlanders in this corps. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at [[Linlithgow]]. \n|-\n|SL\n|Fifeshire Fencibles\n|Facings yellow\n|Colonel James Durham of Largo.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=357}}\n|20 October 1794\n|11 April 1803\n|Served in Ireland. Disbanded at [[Kilkenny]].\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Fraser Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings black\n|Colonel James Fraser of Belladrum.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=357}}\n|29 November 1794\n|12 July 1802\n|Embodied at Inverness. of the soldiers, 300 bore the name of Fraser. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Glasgow. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Glengarry Fencibles|Glengarry]] or British Highland Regiment\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow \n|Colonel Alex. Macdonnell of Glengarry.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=357}}\n|14 August 1794\n|1 July 1802\n|Raised as a Catholic corps. According to General Stewart, more than one-half of the men in this regiment were enlisted from the estate of Glengarry. Of the thirty-two officers, twenty-two were Macdonnells or Macdonalds. Served in Jersey, Guernsey, and in Ireland, where they were actively employed during the rebellion, earning for themselves the sobriquet of the \"Devil's Bloodhounds\".<ref  group=lower-alpha>So called on account of their garb and their unfailing success in hunting down the rebels ({{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=357}} cites {{citation|last=Macdonell |first=Rev. Father Macdonell |authorlink=Ronald MacDonald (bishop)|title=The Glengarry Fencibles |volume=xxvi |journal=Transactions of the Gaelic Society of Inverness}}</ref> Disbanded at Ayr, after which the greater part of the regiment emigrated, together with their families and relations, to Canada, settling in a district to which they gave the name of their native glen.\n\nIn February 1812, a regiment known as the [[Glengarry Light Infantry Fencibles]] was raised in Canada, a proportion of which was made up of soldiers of the former fencible regiment or members of their families.  The colonel of the regiment was [[Edward Baynes (British Army Officer)|E. Baynes]] and a major in the regiment was [[George MacDonnell|George Macdonnell]]. It was disbanded in August 1816.<ref name=Supplement-362>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=362}} Suppliemetal page facing 362</ref>\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Royal Inverness Highlanders]]\n|Highland dress. Initially buff facings, became blue facings when they became the Duke of York's.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}} \n|Colonel John Baillie of Dunean.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=357}}\n|21 November 1794\n|25 August 1802\n|Embodied at Inverness. Served in Ireland during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], and after its suppression the designation of the corps was changed to \"''The Duke of York's Royal Inverness-shire Highlanders''\" as a compliment to their good behaviour. In 1801 the regiment voluntarily offered to serve in any part of the world, but owing to the preliminaries of peace having been signed, their services were not required abroad. Disbanded at Stirling. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Regiment of the Isles, or Macdonald Fencibles]] \n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Alexander, Lord Macdonald.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}} \n|29 May 1798\n|26 July 1802\n|Embodied at Inverness. Served in Scotland and England. Disbanded at Fort George. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Lochaber Fencibles]]\n|Highland dress. Facings black\n|Colonel Donald Cameron of Lochiel.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}}\n|15 June  1798\n|26 June 1802\n|Embodied at Falkirk. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Linlithgow. \n|-\n|SL\n|North Lowland Regiment \n|Facings green.<ref  group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=358}} notes: According to Colonel H. Smith, this corps wore the infantry uniform, with truis</ref>\n|Colonel Thomas Balfour.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}}\n|November 1794\n|6 August 1802\n|There were a number of Highlanders in this corps. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Dundee.\n|-\n|SL\n|West Lowland Regiment.<ref  group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=358}} notes: also known as the \" Western Fencibles.\"</ref>\n|Facings Green.<ref  group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=358}} notes: In Kay's ' Edinburgh Portraits,' vol. ii. p. 330, it is stated that this regiment wore the Highland uniform, \"to which garb the Earl was extremely partial\". According to Colonel Smith, however, the uniform was that of the [[Line regiment|Line]], with truis.</ref>\n|Colonel Earl of Eglinton.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}}\n|2 March 1793\n|26 March 1799\n|Disbanded at Musselburgh.\n|-\n|HS\n|[[Princess Charlotte of Wales' or Loyal Macleod Fencibles]]\n|Highland dress. Facings blue \n|Colonel John Macleod of Colbecks.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}}\n|15 June 1798\n|11 June 1802\n|Embodied at Elgin. Served in Ireland. Disbanded in England at Tynemouth Barracks. \n|-\n|HS\n|The Northern or Gordon Fencibles\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow.<ref  group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=359}} Notes: General Stewart of Garth. This regiment wore black belts (Colonel H. Smith's Mss.)</ref>\n|Colonel Alexander, Duke of Gordon.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=358}}\n|3 March 1793\n|1799\n|Embodied at Aberdeen. Its services were confined to Scotland, but the men having volunteered to extend it, the offer was accepted, and in 1794 the regiment moved to England. \"When quartered in Kent, the King, who had never seen a Highland regiment, ordered them up to London, where they were reviewed in Hyde Park in the presence of His Majesty, who expressed himself highly satisfied with their appearance\".<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=358}} cites General Stewart of Garth</ref> Disbanded in Scotland. \n|-\n|SI\n|Orkney Battalion.\n|Facings yellow\n|Major-Commandant Thomas Balfour.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}}\n|20 April 1793\n|1799\n|Strength, three companies. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Perthshire Fencibles|Perthshire Highlanders]]<ref group=lower-alpha>Also known as \"The Perthshire Regiment of Fencibles\" {{harv|Scobie|1914|p=359}}.</ref> \n|Facings yellow.<ref group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=359}} notes: General Stewart of Garth. The regiment, however, wore the kilt, probably of Robertson tartan. ''Military History, of Perthshire'', p. 176.</ref>\n|Colonel William Robertson of Lude.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}}\n|20 October 1794 \n|27 February 1799\n|Embodied at Perth. \"Although called Perthshire Highlanders, this was a misnomer, as the number of Perthshire Highlanders, or Highlanders of any county, was very limited\".<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=359}} cites General Stewart of Garth</ref> Disbanded at Preston.\n|-\n|SL\n|{{anchor|Prince of Wales Own Fencibles}}Prince of Wales' Own\n|The bonnet and truis. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Sir William Johnstone, Bart.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}}\n|15 June 1798\n|21 May 1802\n|Served in Ireland.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}} May have garrisoned Gibraltar.<ref name=Gibraltar-garrison group=lower-alpha/> Disbanded at Plymouth.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}}\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Reay Highland Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings light grey-blue \n|Colonel Mackay Hugh Baillie of Rosehall.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}} \n|24 October 1794\n|13 October 1802\n|Embodied at Elgin. Served in Ireland. Was present at the battles of [[Battle of Tara Hill|Tara Hill]] and [[battle of Ballinamuck|Ballinamuck]]. Disbanded at Stirling.\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Ross-shire Highland Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Major-Commandant Colin Mackenzie of Mountgerald.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=359}}\n|20 November 1794\n|1799\n|Strength, two companies. Although a small corps, the men were noticeable for their \"exemplary character and physical capacity. No man was punished; none died during its service\".<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=359}} cites General Stewart of Garth.</ref> \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Ross And Cromarty Rangers]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Lewis Mackenzie, Younger of Scatwell.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}} \n|8 August 1798\n|27 July 1802\n|Raised for service in any part of Europe. Embodied at Inverness. Served in Scotland and Ireland. Disbanded at Inverness. \n|-\n|SH\n|[[Rothesay and Caithness Highlanders]]\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow<ref group=lower-alpha>The uniform of this regiment consisted of the red jacket and white waistcoat, red and white hose, buckled shoes, white goatskin purse with black tassels, \"feathered bonnet, with a plaid thrown across the shoulders, and tartan pantaloons, in imitation of the truis, surmounted with a stripe of yellow along the seams, a fringe of tartan on the outside of the thigh, and the same round the ankle\".{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=360}} quoting Stewart of Garth, ''Sketches of the Highlanders'', vol. ii.\n<p>\nIn a rare work, consisting of four quarto pages, compiled by Colonel Sir John Sinclair, and entitled, ''Account of the Rothesay and Caithness Fencibles'', there is an excellent frontispiece illustrating the uniform of the regiment, which is exactly as General Stewart describes it {{harv|Scobie|1914|p=360}}. This \"Account\" was \"particularly addressed to the officers, non-commissioned officers, and private soldiers of the (1st) Battalion, that they might remember they belonged to so respectable a corps\". From it we learn that this battalion might claim the distinction of being the first fencible corps raised for service in Britain, the previous corps being embodied for service in their own country only, ({{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=360}} citing ''Old Scottish Regimental Colours'', by Andrew Ross, S.s.c. , p. 126.).</ref>\n|Colonel Sir John Sinclair of Ulster.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}}\n|\n|\n|2 Battalions.\n|-\n|\n|[[Rothesay and Caithness Highlanders]] \u2014 1st Battalion. \n|\n|Lieutenant-Colonel James, Earl of Caithness.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}}\n|7 March 1794\n|6 May 1799\n|Embodied at Inverness. Remarkable for the size of its officers, twenty of whom averaged six feet in height, and who were consequently known as \"Thier-nan-more\" or \"The great chiefs\". Served in Scotland and the north of England. Disbanded at Bruntsfield Links, Edinburgh.\n|-\n|\n|[[Rothesay and Caithness Highlanders]] \u2014 2nd Battalion. \n|\n|Lieutenant-Colonel Benjamin Williamson.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}}\n|19 November 1794\n|July 1802\n|Embodied at Forfar. Served in Ireland for two years, where it was distinguished for its exemplary conduct. In 1797 this battalion volunteered for service in any part of Europe, but was not called upon to go abroad. Disbanded at Glasgow. \n|-\n|SI\n|Shetland Battalion\n|Facings \u2014\n|Major-Commandant George Malcolmson.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}}\n|8 February 1798\n|1802\n|Strength, two companies. \n|-\n|SL\n|Southern Regiment.<ref group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=360}} notes: Also known as the \"South Fencibles \" or the \"Hopetoun Invincibles\".</ref>\n|Facings Light grey-blue \n|Colonel [[James Hope-Johnstone, 3rd Earl of Hopetoun]].{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=360}}\n|2 March 1793\n|12 April 1799\n|Served in Scotland. Disbanded at Linlithgow.\n|-\n|SH\n|[[Grant or Strathspey Regiment]]\n|Highland dress. Facings green. \n|Colonel Sir James Grant of Grant.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n|2 March 1793\n|April 1799\n|Embodied at Forres. Served in Scotland. Disbanded at Inverness.\n|-\n|SH\n|Sutherland Regiment.\n|Highland dress. Facings yellow\n|Colonel Major-general [[William Wemyss]] of Wemyss.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}} \n|2 March 1793\n|March 1799\n|Embodied at Fort George. Extended its services to Ireland in 1797. Disbanded at Fort George, many of the officers and men transferring their services to the [[93rd Foot|93rd Sutherland Highlanders]], raised by General Wemyss on a letter of service dated 16 April 1799. \n|-\n|\n|Loyal Tarbert Regiment. \n|Facings blue \n|Colonel Sir Edward Leslie, Bart.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n|27 July 1798 \n|19 June 1802\n|Disbanded at Plymouth. \n|-\n|\n|The Loyal Tay Regiment. \n|Facings blue\n|Colonel Sir Robert Anstruther, Bart.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n|25 October 1794\n|28 June 1802\n|This regiment had a good many Highlanders from the Highland borders. Served in Ireland. Disbanded at Stirling. \n|}\n\nThe Scottish Fencibles raised in 1793 had eight companies each, except the Orkney, which had three.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n\nThose raised in 1794\u20131802 had ten companies, except the 1st Battalion Rothesay and Caithness Regiment, which had eight, and three others \u2014 the Angus Volunteers, Ross-shire and Shetland Fencibles \u2014 which had only two companies.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n\nOf the total number of Scottish corps raised from 1739 to 1802, independent of Colonel Macneil's Argyll, Colonel Robertson's Perthshire (both having very few Highlanders), and the Ross-shire Fencibles (which are not included, as their number was small), the total number of Fencibles raised in the Highlands, and considered as exclusively Highland, amounted to twenty-six battalions<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=361}} cites General Stewart of Garth.</ref> Some of the other Scottish Fencibles, however, although not nominally Highland, had a number of men from the Highlands in their ranks, and this fact is noted in the above list under the regiments concerned.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=361}}\n\n===English fencibles===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name||Uniform||Commander||Raised||Disbanded||Notes\n|-\n|Royal Lancashire Volunteers.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}<ref name=Supplement-362/>||Blue facings?{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}}||Sir Thos. Egerton, Bt.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||1779 ||1783||This regiment's services were confined to garrison duty in England.\n|-\n|Royal Lancashire|| ||Lord Grey de Wilton.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||16 October 1794 ||1801\u20132||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Northampton{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||Blue facings red collar.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}}||John Manners Ker.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Loyal Essex{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||  ||John E. Urquhart.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Loyal Nottingham{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||Green facings.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}}||James O'Connor{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794||1801\u20132||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Suffolk{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||John Robinson{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Loyal Somerset{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||Yellow facings.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}}|| W. F. Forster{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|York{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Hon. G. A, C. Stapylton{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||20 October 1794 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Devon and Cornwall{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Robert Hall{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||15 November 1794 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies.\n|-\n|Prince of Wales' Leicester{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| || Major Parkyns{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||15 November 1794 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion\n|-\n|Cheshire{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Charles Courtenay{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||17 November 1794 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies.\n|-\n|Loyal Durham{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||Green facings.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}}||Barrington Price{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||26 February 1795 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies. Served in Ireland during the rebellion \n|-\n|Northumberland Francis{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Blake{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||28 February 1795 ||1801\u20132 ||Ten companies.\n|-\n|Newfoundland{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Skinner{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}||25 April 1795 ||1801\u20132||Ten companies.\n|-\n|Scilly{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Captain Henry Gudgeon{{sfn|British War Office|1797|p=79}}||19 April 1796 ||1801\u20132||One company.<ref>{{harvnb|Cummings|2014}} cites {{citation |title=Court Marshall of Garrison Soldier| newspaper=The Times |date=25 September 1801 |issue=5221}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{anchor|Loyal Surrey Regiment}}Loyal Surrey Regiment.<ref name=Scobie-362-H-Smith>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=362}} notes \"Colonel H. Smith mentions this regiment\".</ref>|| ||Colonel George Augustus Pollen.<ref name=Nat-Archive-1/>||1799 ||1800 ||1794: formation as the [[#Surrey Cavalry|Surrey Cavalry]], From 1800 became the [[#Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers|Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers]].<ref name=Nat-Archive-1>\"1794: formation (Surrey Cavalry); Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry, under Col George Augustus Pollen. From 1800 became the Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers\" {{harv|British National Archive staff|2013|loc=\"Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry\"}}.</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Canadian Volunteers.<ref name=Scobie-362-H-Smith/>|| || ||1799 || ||The regiment was posted to Nova Scotia<ref name=cmhg>{{harvnb|CMHG civil servants|2011|p=1}}</ref>\n|-\n|Fauconberg's  Fencibles.<ref name=Supplement-362/>|| || ||1799 || ||\n|-\n|North's Fencibles.<ref name=Supplement-362/>|| || ||1799 || ||\n|-\n||{{anchor|Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers}}Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers,<ref name=Supplement-362/> or Pollen's Fencibles<ref name=Supplement-362/>|| ||Colonel George Augustus Pollen.<ref name=Nat-Archive-2/>||1800||1802||Ten companies. Previously the [[#Loyal Surrey Regiment|Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry]]. In Nova Scotia.<ref name=Nat-Archive-2>\"Previously the Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry; in Nova Scotia under Col George Augustus Pollen. 1800\u20131802: Loyal Surrey Regiment of Rangers. 1802: disbandment\" {{harv|British National Archive staff|2013a|loc=\"Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry\"}}.</ref>\n|}\n\n===Irish fencibles===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name||Uniform||Commander||Raised||Disbanded||Notes\n|-\n|Loyal Irish (1st Battalion){{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| || Handcock ||15 November 1794|| 1801\u20132||Ten companies.\n|-\n|Loyal Irish (2nd Battalion){{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Handcock ||15 December 1794|| 1801\u20132||Ten companies.\n|- \n|[[135th (Limerick) Regiment of Foot|Loyal Limerick]] {{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||Sir [[Vere Hunt]] ||15 June 1798|| 1801\u20132||Ten companies.\n|-\n|{{anchor|Ancient Irish}}Ancient Irish{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||T. J. Fitzgerald ||4 June 1799||  1801\u20132||Ten companies. The Ancient Irish volunteered for service abroad, and were actually sent to Egypt for a time, taking part in the operations against the French in 1801.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}\n|}\n\n===Welsh fencibles===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name||Uniform||Commander||Raised||Disbanded||Notes\n|-\n|{{anchor|Cambrian Rangers}}Cambrian Rangers{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}}|| ||William Edwards{{sfn|British War Office|1800|p=16}}||8 August 1798 ||1801\u20132|| This regiment was composed of ten companies.{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=362}} It served in the garrison of [[Gibraltar]].<ref name=Gibraltar-garrison group=lower-alpha/>\n|}\n\n===Manx fencibles===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name||Uniform||Commander||Raised||Disbanded||Notes\n|-\n|[[Royal Manx Fencibles|Royal Manx Regiment]] (1st Battalion)|| ||Duke of Atholl.<ref>The Dukes of Atholl held the Sovereignty of the Isle of Man, which had come into their possession in 1736 ({{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=363}} cites {{harvnb|Atholl|Macdonald|1908|p=183}}).</ref>||20 February 1793|| 1801\u20132||Second corps.{{sfn|MNHL staff|2012|p=4}} The 1st Battalion of Manx Fencibles had three companies (for first corps, raised in 1779 see the [[#Manx Fencible Corps|Manx Fencible Corps]] above).\n|-\n|Royal Manx Regiment (2nd Battalion)||Blue facings, fur crest around hat.{{sfn|Reid|2011|p=21}} ||Duke of Atholl||7 April 1795|| 1801\u20132||Second corps.{{sfn|MNHL staff|2012|p=4}} Ten companies. The 2nd Battalion served in Ireland. Some of the men in this battalion were recruited in return and the list of officers shows a few names which suggests a connection with Perthshire.<ref name=Atholl-Macdonald-1908>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=363}} cites {{harvnb|Atholl|Macdonald|1908|p=183}}</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Manx Regiment|| || ||12 July 1803||1811||Third corps.{{sfn|MNHL staff|2012|p=4}} The services performed by this regiment was the defence of the Isle of Man, assisting the Revenue in the prevention of smuggling, and supporting the civil power. The four last companies of the Regiment were raised partly with the view of their supplying volunteers for [[line regiment]]s.{{sfn|Palmerston |1810|p=116}}\n|}\n\n===Further information===\nThree other Fencible Corps may have been raised between 1795\u20131798, which were disbanded in 1801\u20132 viz.:<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n*Royal Birmingham or Rann's Fencibles\n*Nova Scotia Provincial Regiment (for service in Canada), 1803\u20131816: Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, Quebec, Ontario.<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n*Prince Edward's Island Fencibles (for service in Canada)<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n\nIn 1803 four Fencible Corps were raised (probably in the British Isles) for service in Canada. They were:<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n*Newfoundland,  or Skerret's Fencibles,<ref name=Supplement-362/> 1803\u20131816: Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, Quebec, Ontario.<ref name=cmhg/>\n*New Brunswick, or Hunter's Fencibles,<ref name=Supplement-362/> raised in 1803, numbered 104th in 1810, New Brunswick.<ref name=cmhg/>\n*Nova Scotia,  or Wetherall's Fencibles<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n*Canadian Fencible Infantry, or Peter's Fencibles<ref name=Supplement-362/>\nThey were all disbanded in 1816.<ref name=Supplement-362/>\n\nBesides the established regiments there were seven regiments (each of one battalion) for which Letters of Service were issued, but which never appear to have been formed.<ref>{{harvnb|Scobie|1914|p=363}} cites ''History of British Army'', vol. iv., Part II., pp. 943\u2013944.</ref> Five were to have been raised in Scotland and two in England, with a strength of ten companies each:{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=363}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date of letter of service or Order of raising||Colonel or Commissioner||Notes \n|-\n|20 October 1794 ||Lieutenant-Colonel Morison ||\n|-\n|15 November 1794||David Hunter ||\n|-\n|15 June 1798 ||Dunbar || \n|-\n|20 July 1798 ||Dunlop ||\n|-\n|31 July 1798 ||Alex. McGrigor || \n|-\n|10 August 1798 || Tyndale ||\n|-\n|10 December 1798 ||James Kann || \n|}\n\nThe total number of fencible infantry corps embodied 1793\u20131802 was thus 61 battalions of which 29 were Scottish, 15 were English, 4 Irish, 1 Welsh and 2 Manx. \"Most of the Fencible Corps,\" writes Sir [[John Fortescue (military historian)|John Fortescue]] \"were created either in 1794 or 1798, and to judge by the old Monthly Army Lists of 1799, the greatest number of them in existence at one time in Great Britain was 31 regiments of cavalry and 45 battalions of infantry. But by March 1800 the greater part of the cavalry had been disembodied, so that it would not be wise to reckon the Fencibles as exceeding, at their highest figure, twenty to twenty-five thousand men\".{{sfn|Fortescue|1915|pp=889\u2013890}}\n<ref group=lower-alpha>{{harvnb|Fortescue|1915|p=889}} notes: The official list of Auxiliary Forces in 1800 shows 13 regiments of fencible cavalry and 46 battalions of fencible infantry.</ref>\n\nThe preliminaries of peace were signed in London on 1 October 1801. The final ratification of the [[Peace of Amiens]], however, was not concluded until March 1802. Fortescue writes \"most, if not all, of the fencible infantry were disbanded in May 1801, before the signature of the preliminaries of peace\",{{sfn|Fortescue|1915|p=890}} but Ian Scobie states that this was not so, as the greater number were not disbanded until late in 1801 or early in 1802, and that many of the Scottish fencibles, were not disbanded until some time after the Peace of Amiens had been signed (as will be seen from the preceding lists).{{sfn|Scobie|1914|p=364}}\n\nThe disbandment of the fencibles in 1802, and \"the establishment in that year of a permanent Scots Militia, rendered unnecessary any further organisation on a large scale of this more ancient but partial system of national defence\".<ref name=Atholl-Macdonald-1908/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sea Fencibles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|1|group=lower-alpha|refs=\n<ref name=Langford-179>\nA Birmingham recruiting bill for the Warwickshire Regiment of Fencible Light Dragoons {{harv|Langford|1868|p=179}}\n{{quotation|June 2, 1794.\u2014Warwickshire Regiment of Fencible Light Dragoons, commanded by the Earl of Warwick. All high-spirited Young Men, who are able and willing to serve their King and Country, in support of their most excellent and happy Constitution, the Envy of the World, have now a glorious opportunity of shewing their Zeal in the Warwickshire Regiment of Cavalry, to serve only during the present War, and within the Kingdom of Great Britain, to be commanded by the Right Hon. Earl Brooke and Warwick, and other officers of the County.\n<p>\nA Bounty of Five Pounds will be given to each young man who is approved of, and One Guinea to any Person bringing such Recruit.\n<p>\nThey will be all mounted on fine [[Field hunter|Hunter]]s, superior to most Regiments of Light Dragoons.\n<p>\nLet them repair to the Sergeant, at Mr. Owen's, the sign of the Eagle, in Hill Street: and at the Rose and Crown, in Moor Street, where they will enter into present Pay and Good Quarters. God save the King.\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Citation |editor-last=Atholl |editor-first=Katharine Marjory Stewart-Murray, Duchess of |editor2-last=Macdonald |editor2-first=Jane C. C |year=1908  |title=A military history of Perthshire, 1660-1902. |location=Perth |publisher=R.A. & J. Hay |page=183}}\n*{{Citation|author=British National Archive staff |year=2013|title=Old Catalogue:Loyal Surrey Regiment of Fencible Infantry |access-date=15 January 2013|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/Catalogue/topictermdetail.asp?fldAFGroup=4&fldAFTermID=11665&SearchType=5&BackURL=search.asp%3FSearchType%3D5%26fldAFListType%3D2%26fldAFListTermType%3D5%26fldAdvSearchNumber%3D%26fldAFListString%3DLoyal+Surrey+Regiment+of+Fencible+Infantry%26fldAFPartialListString%3D%26fldAFJump%3D%26fldPickTermRow%3D-1}}<!--Validation (source): WO 12; L&I vol 53, 1963; NCA Rules-->\n*{{Citation |author=British National Army Museum staff|year=2013|title=National Army Museum, Study collection: Colonel Thomas Cooper Everitt, with the Hampshire Fencible Cavalry drawn up 