le list|title=May 5, 2016\n|[[Indonesia]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=May 11, 2016\n|[[Chile]]\n|[[Malaysia]]\n|[[South Korea]]\n|[[Thailand]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=May 28, 2016\n|[[Philippines]]\n}}\n| unitssold    = \n| unitsshipped = \n| predecessor  = [[iPhone 5S]]\n| successor    = \n| related      = [[iPhone 5]]<br>[[iPhone 6S]]\n| type         = [[Smartphone]]\n| form         = Slate\n| size         = {{Unbulleted list|{{Nowrap|{{convert|123.8|mm|in|abbr=on}} H}}|{{Nowrap|{{convert|58.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} W}}|{{Nowrap|{{convert|7.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} D}}}}\n| weight       = {{convert|113|g|oz|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"specifications\"/>\n| os = '''Original:''' [[iOS 9#9.3|iOS 9.3]]<br />'''Current:''' [[iOS 13|iOS 13.4.1]], released {{start date|mf=yes|2020|4|7}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/get-your-iphone-and-ipad-ready-for-ios-13-and-ipados-13/ |title = Get your iPhone and iPad ready for iOS 13 and iPadOS 13}}</ref>\n| soc          = [[Apple A9]]<ref name=\"specifications\">{{cite web |author=GSMArena |date=2019 |accessdate=December 22, 2019 |publisher=GSMArena.com |title=Apple iPhone SE - Full phone specifications |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_se-7969.php}}</ref>\n| cpu          = {{Nowrap|1.84 GHz}} dual-core [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARMv8-A]] ''\"Twister\"''<ref name=\"specifications\" />\n| gpu          = [[PowerVR#Series 7XT|PowerVR GT7600]] {{Nowrap|(hexa-core)}}\n| memory       = 2 GB [[LPDDR4]] [[Random-access memory|RAM]]<ref name=\"specifications\"/><ref name=\"9to5mac\">{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Chance|title=First iPhone SE teardown reveals mainly 5s/6s parts inside, but a few surprises too|url=http://9to5mac.com/2016/03/30/iphone-se-teardown/|website=9to5Mac|accessdate=March 31, 2016|date=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n| storage      = 16, 32, 64, or 128 [[Gigabyte|GB]]<ref name=\"specifications\" />\n| battery      = 3.82 [[Volt|V]] 6.21 [[Kilowatt hour|W\u00b7h]] (1,624 [[Ampere-hour|mA\u00b7h]]) [[Lithium polymer battery|Lithium-polymer battery]]<ref name=\"specifications\" />\n| input        = [[Multi-touch]] [[touchscreen]] display, [[Apple motion coprocessors#Apple M9|Apple M9 motion coprocessor]], 3-axis [[gyroscope]], [[accelerometer]], [[digital data|digital]] [[magnetometer|compass]], [[proximity sensor]], [[photodetector|ambient light]] sensor, [[Touch ID]] [[fingerprint reader]]\n| display      = {{convert|4.0|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina Display]], [[LED-backlit LCD display|LED-backlit]] [[IPS panel|IPS LCD]], 1136 \u00d7 640 pixel resolution (326 [[pixels per inch|ppi]]) with full [[sRGB]] standard, 500 cd/m2 max. brightness (typical), 800:1 contrast ratio (typical)  \n| rear_camera  = Backlit [[Sony Exmor RS]] 12 MP (1.22 \u03bcm), [[Flash (photography)|dual-tone LED flash]], [[autofocus]], [[IR filter]], [[burst mode (photography)|burst mode]], f/2.2 [[F-number|aperture]], [[4K resolution|4K]] video recording at {{Nowrap|30 [[frame rate|fps]]}}, [[1080p]] at 30 or {{Nowrap|60 fps}}, [[slow-motion|slow-motion video]] ([[1080p]] at 120 fps and [[720p]] at 240 fps) \n| front_camera = 1.2 MP, f/2.4 [[F-number|aperture]], [[Camera#Exposure control|exposure control]], [[face detection]], auto-[[high-dynamic-range imaging|HDR]], Retina Flash, 720p video recording\n| sound        = Mono speaker, {{Nowrap|3.5 mm}} [[Phone connector (audio)|stereo audio jack]]\n| connectivity = [[Near-field communication|Near-field communication (NFC)]], [[Bluetooth#Bluetooth v4.2|Bluetooth 4.2]], [[GPS]], [[GLONASS]], [[Wi-Fi]] ([[802.11]] [[802.11a|a]]/[[802.11b|b]]/[[802.11g|g]]/[[802.11n|n]]/[[802.11ac|ac]]), [[Voice over LTE|VoLTE]], [[Generic Access Network|Wi-Fi calling]], [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning Port]], {{Nowrap|3.5 mm}} [[Phone connector (audio)|stereo audio jack]]\n| other        = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling \n| sar          = Head SAR: 1.17 W/kg<br />Body SAR: 1.19 W/kg \n| hac          = M3, T4<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 8, 2018 |publisher=Apple Support |title=About Hearing Aid Compatibility (HAC) requirements for iPhone - Apple Support |url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT202186}}</ref> \n| website = {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230142702/http://www.apple.com/iphone-se/ |title=iPhone SE - Apple |date=December 30, 2016}}\n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\n\nThe '''iPhone SE''' (''SE'' meaning ''Special Edition'')<ref name=\"techradar-sename\">{{cite web|title=What the iPhone SE stands for \u2013 and what we think it should stand for|url=http://www.techradar.com/news/phone-and-communications/mobile-phones/what-the-iphone-se-stands-for-and-what-we-think-it-should-stand-for-1317536|website=TechRadar|accessdate=March 21, 2017}}</ref> is a [[smartphone]] that was designed and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is part of the [[List of iOS devices|ninth]] generation of the [[iPhone]] alongside the higher-end {{Nowrap|[[iPhone 6S|iPhone 6S and 6S Plus]]}}. It was announced on March 21, 2016 at the Town Hall auditorium in the [[Apple Campus]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Michael Calore |date=March 10, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |journal=Wired |title=Apple's Spring 2016 Event Will Be Held on Monday, March 21 |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/apple-event-march-2016/}}</ref> by Apple executive Greg Joswiak,<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=March 23, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |publisher=Apple (YouTube.com) |title=Apple - March Event 2016 - YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0wIiDnjz4X4}}</ref> with pre-orders beginning on March 24, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=March 21, 2016 |accessdate=October 6, 2019 |publisher=Apple (apple.com) |title=Apple Introduces iPhone SE \u2014 The Most Powerful Phone with a Four-inch Display - Apple |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2016/03/21Apple-Introduces-iPhone-SE-The-Most-Powerful-Phone-with-a-Four-inch-Display/}}</ref> It was officially released on March 31, 2016.<ref name=\"se_announcement\">{{cite web |author=New Rising Media |date=March 21, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |publisher=New Rising Media (YouTube.com) |title=Apple iPhone SE Announcement - YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pv9ybFJEIrs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Vlad Savov |date=March 21, 2016 |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |publisher=The Verge |title=iPhone SE announced: iPhone 7 specs, iPhone 5S size, $399 price - The Verge |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/21/11254078/apple-iphone-se-announced-size-price-release-date}}</ref> It was re-released almost a year later on March 24, 2017 with larger storage capacities.<ref>{{cite web |author=Chris Welch |date=March 21, 2017 |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |publisher=The Verge |title=Apple doubles iPhone SE storage to 32GB and 128GB - The Verge |url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/3/21/14998660/apple-iphone-se-128gb-announced-pricing-release-date}}</ref> The iPhone SE shares the same physical design and dimensions as the [[iPhone 5S]], but has upgraded internal hardware, including the newer [[Apple A9]] [[System on a chip|system-on-chip]], greater battery capacity, and a 12-megapixel rear camera that can record [[4K resolution|4K]] video at 30 [[Frame rate|frames per second]]. The iPhone SE was discontinued by Apple on September 12, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |author=Benjamin Mayo |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 29, 2018 |publisher=9to5Mac |title=iPhone SE and iPhone 6s no longer sold by Apple (and iPhone X gone too) |url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/09/12/iphone-se-and-iphone-6s-no-longer-sold-by-apple/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Avery Hartmans |date=September 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |publisher=Business Insider Nordic |title=Apple just quietly killed off a bunch of older iPhone and Apple Watch models \u2014 here are the products that are gone forever - Business Insider Nordic |url=https://nordic.businessinsider.com/discontinued-apple-products-iphone-x-iphone-se-apple-watch-edition-2018-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=John McCann |date=September 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |publisher=TechRadar |title=The iPhone SE and iPhone 6S are dead, and that's not good for the iPhone SE 2 |url=https://www.techradar.com/news/the-iphone-se-and-iphone-6s-are-dead-and-thats-not-good-for-the-iphone-se-2}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe previous major redesign of the iPhone, the 4.7-inch [[iPhone 6]] and the 5.5-inch [[iPhone 6|iPhone 6 Plus]], resulted in larger screen sizes. However, a significant number of customers still preferred the smaller 4-inch screen size of the [[iPhone 5]] and the [[iPhone 5S]].\n\nApple stated in the ''[[List of Apple Inc. media events#Apple Special Event (March 21, 2016)|Let us loop you in]]'' event on March 21, 2016 that they sold over 30 million 4-inch iPhones in 2015, further explaining that some people love smaller compact phones. Later in the event, they presented the iPhone SE, describing it as \"the most powerful 4-inch phone ever.\"<ref name=\"se_announcement\"/><ref name=\"wired.com\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/iphone-se-smaller-phone/|title=With the iPhone SE, Apple Returns to a Masterpiece of Design|date=March 22, 2016|work=Wired.com|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ewanspence/2016/03/26/iphone-se-review-very-average-smartphone/|title=iPhone SE Reviews: Apple's Strange Case Of Jekyll And Hyde|date=March 26, 2016|work=Forbes.com|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith a total [[mass]] of 113 [[gram]]s (or 4.0 [[ounce]]s), the iPhone SE is one of the lightest iPhone models released, only surpassed by the iPhone 5S and the iPhone 5 (both having a total mass of 112 grams or 3.95 ounces).\n\nThe iPhone SE, [[iPhone 6S]], and [[iPhone 6S|iPhone 6S Plus]] were the last iPhone models to feature a standard 3.5&nbsp;mm [[Phone connector (audio)|stereo headphone jack]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Adnan Farooqui |date=September 17, 2018 |accessdate=October 8, 2018 |publisher=Ubergizmo |title=Apple Discontinues The iPhone 6S And iPhone SE As Well |url=https://www.ubergizmo.com/2018/09/apple-discontinues-iphone-6s-and-iphone-se/}}</ref>\n\nNo affordable successor to the iPhone SE was announced during the September 12, 2018 ''[[List of Apple Inc. media events#Apple Special Event (September 12, 2018)|Apple Special Event]]'', and ''[[Business Insider]]'' stated that \"Apple made a big mistake by removing its smallest and most affordable iPhone from its lineup\", suggesting that the company was disregarding a significant number of [[customer]]s who had been worried over the loss of the smaller design.<ref>{{cite web |author=Dave Smith |date=September 18, 2018 |accessdate=September 22, 2018|publisher=Business Insider Nordic |title=Apple made a big mistake by killing the iPhone SE, its smallest and most affordable smartphone - Business Insider Nordic |url=https://nordic.businessinsider.com/apple-iphone-se-vs-iphone-xs-2018-9}}</ref> This was affirmed by ''[[Computerworld]]'', who claimed that \"the harsh reality is that across some of Apple's biggest markets, wage growth has stagnated, and people are feeling the pinch\", further stating that there will always exist [[consumer]]s in the mid-tier smartphone markets.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jonny Evans |date=February 20, 2019 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |publisher=Computerworld |title=People like iPhone SE, but Apple doesn't seem to care |url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/3342200/mobile-wireless/people-like-iphone-se-but-apple-doesnt-seem-to-care.html}}</ref>\n\nIn relation with the discontinuation of the iPhone SE, ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' mentioned on September 22, 2018, that women and other smartphone users with smaller hands have reported \"pain from holding, scrolling, and swiping on phones, and a review of research on the [[ergonomics]] of handheld devices concludes that bigger products, like large phones and tablets, often result in overextension of the thumb and wrist\", hinting to [[repetitive strain injury]], and that oversized iPhones and smartphones in general can be physically unusable for some users.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jane C. Hu |date=September 22, 2018 |accessdate=September 29, 2018|publisher=Quartz |title=Apple's iPhone XS, XR, and XS Max are bad news for women\u2014and anyone else with smaller hands \u2014 Quartz |url=https://qz.com/1391034/apples-iphone-xs-xr-and-xs-max-are-bad-news-for-women-and-anyone-else-with-smaller-hands/}}</ref> The technology website ''[[Gizmodo]]'' shared the same concern, hoping that \"there will be a return to smaller phones\", and expressed a desire \"to hold one's phone in a single hand, and be able to use it fully.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Logan Booker |date=October 1, 2018 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |publisher=Gizmodo Australia |title=Why I Just Bought An iPhone SE |url=https://www.gizmodo.com.au/2018/10/why-i-just-bought-an-iphone-se/}}</ref>\n\nOn January 19, 2019 the iPhone SE was back on sale as a clearance item for $249.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Jon Fingas|date=19 January 2019|accessdate=19 January 2019|publisher=[[Engadget]]|title=iPhone SE goes back on sale as a $249 clearance item|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/01/19/apple-iphone-se-back-on-sale-clearance/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Andrew Liptak|date=19 January 2019|accessdate=19 January 2019|publisher=[[The Verge]]|title=Apple is once again selling its iPhone SE \u2014 for now|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119230226/https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/19/18189785/apple-iphone-se-on-sale-clearance|archivedate=19 January 2019|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/19/18189785/apple-iphone-se-on-sale-clearance}}</ref> However, by January 20, 2019 stock was sold out.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Joe Rossignol|date=19 January 2019|accessdate=20 January 2019|publisher=[[MacRumors]]|title=Apple Begins Selling iPhone SE Again on Clearance Store, Starting at $249 Brand New [Sold Out]|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2019/01/19/iphone-se-clearance-special-249/}}</ref> On February 20, 2019 ''[[TechRadar]]'' announced that the iPhone SE once again was on sale as a clearance item with a $100 price reduction. The price for the 32 GB version was $249, while the price for the 128 GB version was $299. The iPhones were unlocked, with [[AT&T]], [[T-Mobile]], or [[Verizon Communications|Verizon]] as optional [[SIM card]] [[Mobile network operator|carriers]]. It was available in all original colors, including Space Gray, Silver, Gold, and Rose Gold.<ref>{{cite web |author=Mackenzie Frazier |date=February 20, 2019 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |publisher=TechRadar |title=The iPhone SE is back at Apple and it's on clearance for $100 off |url=https://www.techradar.com/news/the-iphone-se-is-back-at-apple-and-its-on-clearance-for-dollar100-off}}</ref><ref name=\"CNET\">{{cite web |author=Steven Musil |date=March 7, 2019 |accessdate=March 10, 2019 |publisher=CNET.com |title=The iPhone SE is once again available from Apple -- for $249 - CNET |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-se-is-again-available-from-apple-for-249-march-7/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Alex Wagner |date=March 8, 2019 |accessdate=March 10, 2019 |publisher=TmoNews.com |title=Apple selling iPhone SE with T-Mobile SIM, clearance pricing starts at $249 - TmoNews |url=https://www.tmonews.com/2019/03/apple-iphone-se-t-mobile-sim-price-249/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Ricky |date=March 8, 2019 |accessdate=March 10, 2019 |publisher=GSMArena.com |title=iPhone SE on clearance at Apple's website starting at $249 in the US - GSMArena.com news |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/iphone_se_on_clearance_at_apples_website_starting_at_249_in_the_us-news-35934.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Anton D. Nagy |date=March 9, 2019 |accessdate=March 10, 2019 |publisher=Pocketnow.com |title=Apple iPhone SE back in stock on Apple's Clearance website |url=https://pocketnow.com/apple-iphone-se-clearance}}</ref> On March 25, 2019 ''Gizmodo'' reported that the iPhone SE was back in Apple's clearance shop, and added that \"it's likely the last of Apple's stock that the company has finally put on clearance.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Adam Clark Estes |date=March 25, 2019 |accessdate=March 30, 2019 |publisher=Gizmodo.com |title=iPhone SE Returns to Apple Store for as Little as $250 |url=https://gizmodo.com/the-iphone-se-is-back-in-the-apple-store-and-its-cheap-1833540632/amp}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n=== Design ===\nThe exterior design of the iPhone SE is nearly identical to that of the iPhone 5 and the iPhone 5S, with the exception of [[Diffuse reflection|matte]]-[[chamfer]]ed edges and an inset [[stainless steel]] rear Apple logo. The iPhone SE shares the same physical sizes and dimensions, so cases designed to fit the 5 and the 5S will also fit an {{Nowrap|iPhone SE}}.<ref name=\"macworld-cases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macworld.com/article/3046633/apple-phone/yes-your-old-iphone-5s-case-will-fit-on-the-new-iphone-se.html|title=Yes, your old iPhone 5s case will fit on the new iPhone SE|website=Macworld|publisher=IDG|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=2016-03-21}}</ref> The iPhone SE was available in the colors Space Gray, Silver, Gold, and Rose Gold.<ref name=\"geekcom-se\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name !!Front      \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#808086\"| ||Space Gray ||Black\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#d3d3d6\" |  ||Silver ||White\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#e6be86\" |  ||Gold ||White\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#ffc0c6\" |  ||Rose Gold ||White\n|}\n\n=== Hardware ===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the [[Apple A9]] [[System on a chip|system-on-chip]] (SoC) with an [[Apple M9|M9]] [[motion coprocessor]] and supports [[near field communication]] for [[Apple Pay]]. It was originally released with {{Nowrap|16 GB}} or {{Nowrap|64 GB}} of internal storage. It features a {{Nowrap|12 megapixel}} rear-facing camera with the ability to record 4K video at 30 [[Frame rate|frames per second]]. Unlike the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus, the SE does not include [[3D Touch]], nor the updated faster second-generation [[Touch ID]] sensor from the 6s and 6s Plus,<ref name=\"phonearena-removed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/Apple-iPhone-SE-TouchID-is-the-same-as-in-5s-much-slower-than-iPhone-6s-fingerprint-sensor_id79522|title=Apple iPhone SE TouchID is the same as in 5s, same as the iPhone 6s fingerprint sensor|last1=H.|first1=Victor|date=March 21, 2016|work=PhoneArena|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> or its [[barometer]].<ref name=\"cnet-disadvantages\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnet.com/how-to/iphone-se-vs-iphone-6s-features/|title=5 features you don't get with the iPhone SE|website=CNET|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2017 Apple announced that it would double the storage for these models at the same launch prices. The upgraded models were released on March 24, 2017 with 32 GB or 128 GB of internal storage.<ref name=\"verge-storagedouble\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/3/21/14998660/apple-iphone-se-128gb-announced-pricing-release-date|title=Apple doubles iPhone SE storage to 32GB and 128GB|website=The Verge|accessdate=March 21, 2017|date=2017-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"ars-7andSEbump\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2017/03/minor-iphone-bump-turns-the-7-and-7-plus-red-and-gives-iphone-se-more-storage/|title=Minor iPhone bump turns the 7 and 7 Plus red, gives iPhone SE more storage|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=March 21, 2017|date=2017-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter the introduction of [[iOS 13]], the iPhone SE (along with all supported [[iOS]]- and [[iPadOS]]-devices) supports Apple\u2019s replacement for [[3D Touch]], known as [[Force Touch|Haptic Touch]]. Haptic Touch is similar to 3D Touch, but it is software-based, which means that previous pressure-sensitive touch-inputs have now been replaced by long-press touch-inputs.<ref>{{Citation|title=Tour of iPhone SE on iOS 13!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zqYHAYh80oA|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Software ===\n{{See also|iOS|iOS 9|iOS 10|iOS 11|iOS 12|iOS 13}}\nThe iPhone SE originally shipped with {{Nowrap|[[iOS 9.3]]}}, supporting [[iPhone 6]]- and [[iPhone 6S|6S]]-exclusive features such as [[Apple Pay]], Live Photos, Retina Flash, and always-on [[Siri]] voice activation.<ref name=\"geekcom-se\">{{cite web|title=Apple shows off 4-inch iPhone SE, iOS 9.3|url=http://www.geek.com/apple/apple-shows-off-4-inch-iphone-se-ios-9-3-1650259/|website=Geek.com|publisher=Ziff Davis|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=2016-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet-disadvantages\"/><ref name=\"verge-versus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/21/11277512/apple-iphone-se-6s-6-comparison-specs-price-guide|title=iPhone SE vs. iPhone 6 and 6S: which Apple smartphone should you get?|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=2016-03-21}}</ref> The SE is compatible with iOS 13.<ref name=ios12-se>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/ios/ios-13/|title=iOS 13: More power to you.|website=Apple.com|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=September 21, 2018}}</ref> During the [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference|WWDC]] 2019 Keynote, Apple announced that the iPhone SE will support most of the main features of [[iOS 13]]. This includes the new [[Light-on-dark color scheme|dark mode]] (which aims to reduce [[eye strain]]), and Low Data Mode<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |publisher=Apple Support |title=Use Low Data Mode on iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch - Apple Support |url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT210596}}</ref> for restricting background network (both [[Wi-Fi]] and [[Cellular network|mobile network]]) usage.<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=June 4, 2019 |accessdate=June 10, 2019 |publisher=Apple (YouTube.com) |title=WWDC 2019 Keynote \u2014 Apple |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=psL_5RIBqnY}}</ref>\n\n[[File:iPhone SE rose gold rear.png | thumb|220x124px | right | The rear of an iPhone SE in Rose Gold color finish.]]\n\n== Reception ==\n''[[CNET]]'' was positive, considering the iPhone SE to be a \"great choice at the small end, with no compromises\".<ref name=\"ars-7andSEbump\" /> ''CNET'' also lauded Apple for accomplishing the task of adapting the 6S's hardware to three different form factors; the smaller 4.0-inch SE, 4.7-inch 6S, and 5.5-inch 6S Plus.<ref name=\"cnet-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/products/apple-iphone-se-review/|title=Apple iPhone SE review: Small wonder|website=CNET|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ars-7andSEbump\" /> In a later article, ''CNET'' summarized the iPhone SE to be \u201cthe smaller, more pocketable member of the iPhone family. It was Apple's compact, budget option, and its 4-inch screen and tinier overall size were total throwback stuff. Consumers loved the battery life and that it still had a headphone jack.\u201d<ref name=\"CNET\" />\n\n''[[The Verge]]'' considered the iPhone SE to be \"a much-improved, well-designed, small phone with great battery life\" and a \"great upgrade\" for existing owners of the 4S or 5S models, noting the device's familiar form factor, high performance (going as far as considering the screen size itself to be the only hindrance to multitasking and certain apps), and improved battery life. Giving the device an 8.7 out of 10, Goode argued that \"the iPhone SE is not a tiny little engine of innovation. It's today's tech in yesterday's phone body. As with anything, we should be wary of giving too much praise to something that's just doing its job.\"<ref name=\"verge-sereview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/25/11302968/apple-iphone-se-review|title=iPhone SE review: today's tech, yesterday's design|last1=Goode|first1=Lauren|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=September 28, 2016|date=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n\n''[[TechCrunch]]'' admired the iPhone SE's design and mentioned that the phone appealed \"not just to the nostalgic and neophobic, but simply people who prefer a smaller phone. I don't have particularly large or small hands, but I preferred this highly pocketable, proven design to the new one for a number of reasons\", describing the phone further as \"the best object Apple ever designed, filled with the best tech it had ever developed. It was the best phone ever made.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Devin Coldewey |date=September 14, 2018 |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |publisher=TechCrunch |title=The iPhone SE was the best phone Apple ever made, and now it's dead |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/09/14/the-iphone-se-was-the-best-phone-apple-ever-made-and-now-its-dead/}}</ref>\n\n''GSMArena'' mentioned that the iPhone SE \"struck the right balance between size, cost, and performance\" and that it \"helped Apple sell more phones than predicted in the summer of 2016, helping it beat analysts expectations and was strategic for Apple in price-sensitive markets such as India and China where Apple struggles to match its success from Western markets.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Paul |date=September 23, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |publisher=GSMArena |title=RIP Apple iPhone SE - GSMArena.com news |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/rip_iphone_se-news-33335.php}}</ref>\n\n''Tom's Guide'' acclaimed the iPhone SE for being an affordable and compact smartphone with a headphone jack. Stating that \u201ceven worse than holding a big phone is carrying it around. When I'm done holding my iPhone SE \u2014 comfortably \u2014 I can slip it into the pocket of jeans, and almost forget that it's there. That's simply not possible with a big-screen device, which adds considerable bulk and bulge no matter how thin phone makers try to squeeze it.\u201d, praising the possibility and practicality to \u201csimultaneously charge my phone and listen to music\u201d, and reported that \u201csmartphone sales are stalling, Apple's included. Perhaps in an effort to find some way \u2014 any way \u2014 to convince people to buy a new phone, Apple might figure it needs to build a device that appeals to us, compact phone devotees.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |author=Philip Michaels |date=January 21, 2019 |accessdate=February 24, 2019 |publisher=Tom's Guide |title=Why I'm Still Using the iPhone SE |url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/why-i-use-an-iphone-se,review-6102.html}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Next Web]]'' described Apple\u2019s iPhone SE as \u201cthe best looking phone it's ever made\u201d, further mentioning that \u201cthe SE is essentially an iPhone 6S fitted into the compact, beautifully designed body of the iPhone 5 from 2012. It\u2019s one of the only phones you could get with a bead-blasted aluminum body. I owned a 5S for years, and loved using it without a case because I couldn\u2019t get enough of that unique satin finish and the classy chamfered edges. And after switching to Android some years ago, and having switched between dozens of phones over the past few years as a reviewer, I sorely miss the sort of attention to detail that these older iPhones showcased.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |author=Abhimanyu Ghoshal |date=January 22, 2019 |accessdate=February 24, 2019 |publisher=TNW (The Next Web) |title=I'm kicking myself for not buying an iPhone SE last weekend |url=https://thenextweb.com/plugged/2019/01/22/im-kicking-myself-for-not-buying-an-iphone-se-last-weekend/}}</ref>\n\n''[[Macworld]]'' called the iPhone SE a \"pocket-size powerhouse\", and described its 4-inch screen as \"easier to reach with your thumb while you\u2019re holding the phone one-handed\". The smaller size was described as \"the biggest deal for me when using this iPhone. Suddenly I could drop my phone into any pocket again (pockets on women\u2019s pants are small too), and comfortably reach the whole screen\", further describing the iPhone SE as \"powerful, speedy, and a worthy addition to the low end of the lineup.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Susie Ochs |date=March 31, 2016 |accessdate=August 24, 2019 |publisher=Macworld (Macworld.com) |title=iPhone SE review: Features, Specifications, and Pricing |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3049962/iphone-se-review-its-a-pocket-size-powerhouse.html}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of models==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of iOS devices]]\n*[[History of iPhone]]\n*[[Comparison of smartphones]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = iPhone SE\n | before = [[iPhone 5S]]\n | after = None\n | years = 9th generation\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{iPhone}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2016]]\n[[Category:Discontinued smartphones]]\n", "name_user": "2601:285:c180:e90:446e:3f93:434b:b4e4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_SE"}
{"title_page": "Killycluggin", "text_new": "{{Refimprove | date = March 2017}}\n{{cleanup list|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Killycluggin Stone.jpg|thumb|Killycluggin Stone]]\n\n'''Killycluggin''' ({{Irish derived place name| 'Coil a Chlog\u00e1in', meaning \"the Wood of the Bell-Shaped Stone\"}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish area of [[Templeport]] and the barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nKillycluggin is bounded on the north by [[Tonyhallagh]] townland, on the west by [[Lissanover]] townland, on the east by [[Tonyrevan]] townland and on the south by [[Bellaheady]] townland in Kildallan parish and by [[Kilnavert]] and [[Corran, County Cavan]] townlands. Killycluggin's chief geographical features are a stream, a stone quarry and a gravel pit. Killycluggin is traversed by the [[R205 road (Ireland)]], minor roads, rural lanes and the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. The townland covers 76 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nUntil the 1652 Cromwellian Settlement of Ireland, the modern townland of [[Tonyrevan]] formed part of the townland of Killycluggin. The 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Killcloggin''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf|title=National Archives Dublin|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html|title=Templeport Development Association - 1609 Baronial-Map|publisher=}}</ref> A 1610 grant spells it as ''Kilclogen''. A 1630 Inquisition spells it as ''Kilcloghan''. The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Killerluggin''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Killycraggan''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\nKillycluggin was the site of the pre-Christian pagan god of Ireland [[Crom Cruach]], the [[Killycluggin Stone]], situated in a stone circle on Bannon\u2019s farm in the townland.\n\nIn the Plantation of Ulster by grant dated 23 June 1610, along with other lands, King James VI and I granted two polls of ''Kilclogen'' to Hugh Culme, esquire, as part of the Manor of Calva.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194&dq=Kilclogen&source=bl&ots=sGT6qXkfxh&sig=9RJ9eMs-ATQuJW4vgmqxm_501_Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjrp7WOoqzfAhUIDuwKHYsRAHMQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kilclogen&f=false]</ref> Culme then surrendered his interest in Killycluggin to Walter Talbot of Ballyconnell. Walter Talbot died on 26 June 1625 at Ballyconnell and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Killycluggin lands aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan Town on 20 September 1630 stated that Walter Talbot's lands included two polls in ''Kilcloghan''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=false}]</ref> James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore of Maryland, USA, in 1635 and had a son Colonel George Talbot who owned an estate in Cecil County, Maryland which he named Ballyconnell in honour of his native town in Cavan. George Talbot was appointed Surveyor-General of Maryland in 1683. In the aftermath of the Irish Rebellion of 1641, James Talbot's estate in Ballyconnell was confiscated in the Cromwellian Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652 because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. The Talbot lands in Killycluggin were distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland as belonging to ''Captain Gwilliams'' (i.e. the landlord of Ballyconnell, Captain Thomas Gwyllym) and the tenants as ''Edward Rely & Others''. \n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were three Hearth Tax payers in- ''Kilclagan- Dorby Don, John Reade and Thomas Teddy''.\n\nGwyllym later sold the land to John Blachford who was born in 1598 in Ashmore, Dorset, England, the son of Richard and Frances Blachford. He became a merchant in Dorchester, Dorset but fled to France in 1633 when facing a warrant from the Exchequer for not paying customs. He married Mary Renald from Devon and died at Lissanover, County Cavan in 1661 and was buried at St. Orvins in Dublin (probably [[St. Audoen's Church, Dublin (Church of Ireland)]]),  despite wishing to be buried back in Dorchester. His will was published on 9 January 1665 leaving his son John Blachford as his sole heir. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 21 May 1667 found that his widow Mary Blachford and his heir John were seized of, inter alia, the land of Killeclogine alias Killecragan. He had sons John, Thomas, Ambrose and William (who became a Major) and daughters Mary and Frances. Major William Blachford was born in 1658 and died at Lissanover on 28 March 1727. The Blachford family gravestones in Templeport Church read as follows- This monument was erected by MAJOR WILLIAM / BLASHFORD of Lisnover in 1721 to the memory of / his father, JOHN BLASHFORD, late of the same Esqr. but / from Dorchester in Dorsetshire, the place of his / nativity, who in his lifetime chose this for a burying / place, for himself and family, but died in Dublin / was buried in St. Orvins Church but his wife, MARY / RENALD of a Devonsheire family is buried here / as also three sons and two daughters, viz JOHN / AMBROSE AND THOMAS; MARY AND FRANCES / Here likewise lies buried two wives of MAJOR WILLIAM BLASHFORD, son to the said JOHN BLASHFORD viz / MARY MAGHEE of an ancient Family in Lincolnsheire. CORNET CHIDLEY BLACHFORD, son to MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD, leys buried here who dyed August ye 29th, 1722. This aboue MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD. / That erected this monument, died the 28th of March 1727, aged 69 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/memorialspage/Blachford-Memorial-detail.htm |title=Blachford Memorial detail |website=St Peter's Church Templeport  |access-date=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA deed dated 10 May 1744 spells the name as ''Killiclogan''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=78971 | title=Memorial No: 78971 | publisher=Registry of Deeds Index Project Ireland | accessdate=22 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Kilclogan''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list four tithe payers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killyclugan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killydugan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killylugan&search=Search],  in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Killycluggin Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1841.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=killycluggin&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 62, being 31 males and 31 females. There were thirteen houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 56, being 29 males and 27 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were twelve houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists sixteen landholders in the townland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191183&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EKillycluggin%3C/b%3E|title=Griffith's Valuation|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 53, being 29 males and 24 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=107;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 36, being 22 males and 14 females. There were nine houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/op1250167-1001]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 53, being 28 males and 25 females. There were nine houses in the townland, all were inhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n295/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 51, being 27 males and 24 females. There were eight houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=296&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there were ten families listed in the townland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Killyclifin/|title=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1901|publisher=}}</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there were only nine families listed in the townland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Killycluggin/|title=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\n# A Neolithic Stone Circle (Site number 62 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated 10m WNW of the site of the celebrated Killycluggin Stone (93). Much disturbed. Subcircular raised area (int. dims. 22m E-W; 18.6m N-S) enclosed by a total of eighteen stones, all but five of which have fallen. The site is divided into two unequal portions by a field boundary running N-S. The smaller portion, W of this, is defined by four orthostats still in position. The largest stone (now fallen) is at NNE (L 3.93m; dims. 1.45m x 0.68m). (\u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in 1979, 155; Killanin and Duignan 1989, 61)''.) <ref>''Antiquities of the Irish Countryside'' by Se\u00e1n P. \u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in (1979), p.55</ref><ref>''The Shell Guide to Ireland'', by Lord Killanin, M.V. Duignan and Peter Harbison (Editor) (1989), p.61.</ref>\n# A La T\u00e8ne decorated standing stone called the [[Killycluggin Stone]] or the [[Crom Cruach]] Stone [http://www.templeport.ie/magh-slecht-dara-fort/plain-of-blood.pd]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} which was originally situated in the above stone circle but is now in [[Cavan County Museum]][http://www.megalithicireland.com/Killycluggin%20Stone,%20Cavan%20Museum.html] [http://www.irishmegaliths.org.uk/zKillycluggin1.htm](Site number 93 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''The Killycluggin stone is a fragmentary decorated monolith of Iron Age date that was first brought to general public notice in 1922 (Macalister 1922). At that time the stone was in the same broken state in which it now appears and was situated some 10m SE of a stone circle (CV013-026002-). Macalister recorded local traditions which alleged that the damage to the stone had been carried out in living memory by local farmers in order to remove an obstruction to agricultural activities. Macalister also stated that people of the vicinity had dug around the stone in a vain search for buried treasure and in so doing had apparently destroyed a 'cist burial'. He did not, however, actually see this 'cist burial'. Some thirty years later a second decorated stone fragment, probably a portion of the same monolith, was discovered a short distance down-slope from the main piece. In the early summer of 1974 it was decided to remove the weathered and overgrown fragments to the National Museum of Ireland. A limited excavation was undertaken in its immediate vicinity which revealed that 'the stone stood in a flat-bottomed pit which had been deliberately sunk 80cm into the subsoil to receive it' (Raftery 1978, 51-2). Immediately E of the stone were two pits one of which may be identified as the remains of the cist burial identified by Macalister as it contained tiny fragments of burnt bone (CV013-026003-). The two fragments of the Killycluggin Stone are on display in the Cavan County Museum, Ballyjamesduff, while a replica stands at the cross-roads c. 250m NW of the original site. The following description of the stone is derived from Raftery (1978, 49-51). The main fragment has been worked to more-or-less cylindrical form on its surviving upper portion. That part which was intended to be below ground level is rough and irregular and projects awkwardly in one direction so that the stone as a whole is crudely L-shaped. The base of the stone slopes obliquely to its vertical axis. The entire upper surface of this stone had been smashed by deliberate and systematic hammering. This destruction continued along one side, whereby the ornament, down to the base of the stone was totally obliterated. The surviving ornament, which comprises combinations of sweeping curves and tight, hair-spring spirals \u2013 classic La T\u00e8ne motifs \u2013 is chiseled deeply and crisply into the prepared surface of the stone. The curvilinear patterns have been divided into rectangular panels by straight vertical lines and by horizontal lines at right angles to them which define the basal extremity of the ornamented area. The precise original width of only one such panel can now be ascertained (c. 0.9m wide and 0.75m high) but it may be estimated that four such panels of decoration once existed on the stone giving an original circumference of 3.6m. The smaller decorated fragment appears to represent a portion of the dome-shaped top of the original monolith and, in this regard, would have resembled that of the best known of the Irish aniconic stones, the stele from Turoe, Co. Galway (GA097-152----). The decoration on this fragment is of two types. Along one edge slight remains of curvilinear patterns, similar to those on the portion just described, survive. Sufficient remains to show that the upper limits of this decoration are defined by a straight line as is the case at the base of the stone, and traces of one of the lines which divide the ornament into vertical, rectangular panels are present here too. The convex upper surface of this fragment is decorated by a series of deeply chiseled, parallel lines which extend across the surface of the stone. The surviving edges of this panel of ornament are defined by a straight line which is incised at an oblique angle to the line which forms the boundary to the zones of curvilinear ornament. Thus there occurs what is now a triangular area, devoid of ornament between the ornament on the apex of the stone and the ornament on the surviving cylindrical part. The two decorated fragments do not join so that neither the original height of the stone nor the precise overall disposition of its ornamentation can now be ascertained. (O\u2019Donovan 1995, no. 93 with further references) The Killycluggin Ornamented stones are subject to a preservation order made under the National Monuments Acts 1930 to 2014 (PO no. 17/1933). References: 1. Macalister, R.A.S. 1922 On a stone with La T\u00e8ne decoration recently discovered in Co. Cavan. Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland 52, 113-16. 2. O'Donovan, P.F. 1995 Archaeological inventory of county Cavan. Dublin. Stationery Office. 3. Raftery, B. 1978 Excavations at Killycluggin, county Cavan. Ulster Journal of Archaeology 41, 49-54.''.) <ref name=\"auto\">''On a Stone with La T\u00e8ne Decoration Recently Discovered in Co. Cavan'', by R. A. S. Macalister, in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Sixth Series, Vol. 12, No. 2 (31 Dec. 1922), pp. 113-116.</ref><ref>''Excavations at Killycluggin, County Cavan'' by Barry Raftery, in Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Third Series, Vol. 41 (1978), pp. 49-54.</ref><ref>''Fragment of the Killycluggin Stone'' by Se\u00e1n P. \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in, in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Vol. 82, No. 1 (1952), p. 68</ref>\n# A [[Bronze Age]] stone cist discovered when excavating the Killycluggin Stone (Site number 165 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995) <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n# A Megalithic Tomb (Site number 46 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''There are three set stones here. A large stone, 1.8m by 0.25m by 1m high, is aligned E-W. To the S and at right angles to its W end is a second stone, 1.25m by 0.25m by 0.4m in exposed height. The third stone, 0.7m W of the S end of the last, is aligned E-W and measures 0.6m by 0.4m by 0.6m high. This configuration of stones may represent the remains of some form of megalithic monument. Field-clearance debris has been heaped around it. (Davies, ITA Survey, Co. Cavan 1941)''.)\n# An earthen ring-fort (Site number 775 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Raised oval area (int. dims. c. 56m NNE-SSW; c. 40m WNW-ESE) enclosed by two substantial earthen banks with wide, deep, partly waterlogged intermediate fosse. From E-S-SW the external bank has been modified and incorporated into the field boundary. From NNW-N-NE the inner bank has been removed and replaced by a modern field boundary. An earlier report (OPW 1969) suggested that the original entrance may have been at WSW. Densely overgrown with vegetation''.)\n# An earthen ring-fort (Site number 774 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- '' Not marked on any OS ed. Raised oval area (int. dims. 35m E-W; 29.2m N-S) divided into two roughly equal portions by the now disused Cavan-Leitrim railway. The portion WNW of this is enclosed by a low much-disturbed bank of earth and stone. Projecting into the internal area from the inner face of the bank at WNW are possible remains of a souterrain (CV013-027002-). The portion ESE of the railway has been largely levelled but its outline is readily identifiable. Original entrance not recognisable''.)\n# An underground [[Souterrain]] discovered in ring-fort No. 774 above (Site number 1244 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated within Killycluggin rath (CV013-027001-). A long, deep depression (L7.7m; Wth 1.8m; D 1m) projecting into the interior from the inner face of the bank of the rath at WNW, may represent a collapsed souterrain''.)\n# A Lime kiln\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.07514|-7.810271|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove | date = March 2017}}\n{{cleanup list|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Killycluggin Stone.jpg|thumb|Killycluggin Stone]]\n\n'''Killycluggin''' ({{Irish derived place name| 'Coil a Chlog\u00e1in', meaning \"the Wood of the Bell-Shaped Stone\"}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish area of [[Templeport]] and the barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nKillycluggin is bounded on the north by [[Tonyhallagh]] townland, on the west by [[Lissanover]] townland, on the east by [[Tonyrevan]] townland and on the south by [[Bellaheady]] townland in Kildallan parish and by [[Kilnavert]] and [[Corran, County Cavan]] townlands. Killycluggin's chief geographical features are a stream, a stone quarry and a gravel pit. Killycluggin is traversed by the [[R205 road (Ireland)]], minor roads, rural lanes and the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. The townland covers 76 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nUntil the 1652 Cromwellian Settlement of Ireland, the modern townland of [[Tonyrevan]] formed part of the townland of Killycluggin. The 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Killcloggin''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf|title=National Archives Dublin|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html|title=Templeport Development Association - 1609 Baronial-Map|publisher=}}</ref> A 1610 grant spells it as ''Kilclogen''. A 1630 Inquisition spells it as ''Kilcloghan''. The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Killerluggin''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Killycraggan''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\nKillycluggin was the site of the pre-Christian pagan god of Ireland [[Crom Cruach]], the [[Killycluggin Stone]], situated in a stone circle on Bannon\u2019s farm in the townland.\n\nIn the Plantation of Ulster by grant dated 23 June 1610, along with other lands, King James VI and I granted two polls of ''Kilclogen'' to Hugh Culme, esquire, as part of the Manor of Calva.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194&dq=Kilclogen&source=bl&ots=sGT6qXkfxh&sig=9RJ9eMs-ATQuJW4vgmqxm_501_Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjrp7WOoqzfAhUIDuwKHYsRAHMQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kilclogen&f=false]</ref> Culme then surrendered his interest in Killycluggin to Walter Talbot of Ballyconnell. Walter Talbot died on 26 June 1625 at Ballyconnell and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Killycluggin lands aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan Town on 20 September 1630 stated that Walter Talbot's lands included two polls in ''Kilcloghan''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=false}]</ref> James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore of Maryland, USA, in 1635 and had a son Colonel George Talbot who owned an estate in Cecil County, Maryland which he named Ballyconnell in honour of his native town in Cavan. George Talbot was appointed Surveyor-General of Maryland in 1683. In the aftermath of the Irish Rebellion of 1641, James Talbot's estate in Ballyconnell was confiscated in the Cromwellian Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652 because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. The Talbot lands in Killycluggin were distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland as belonging to ''Captain Gwilliams'' (i.e. the landlord of Ballyconnell, Captain Thomas Gwyllym) and the tenants as ''Edward Rely & Others''. \n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were three Hearth Tax payers in- ''Kilclagan- Dorby Don, John Reade and Thomas Teddy''.\n\nGwyllym later sold the land to John Blachford who was born in 1598 in Ashmore, Dorset, England, the son of Richard and Frances Blachford. He became a merchant in Dorchester, Dorset but fled to France in 1633 when facing a warrant from the Exchequer for not paying customs. He married Mary Renald from Devon and died at Lissanover, County Cavan in 1661 and was buried at St. Orvins in Dublin (probably [[St. Audoen's Church, Dublin (Church of Ireland)]]),  despite wishing to be buried back in Dorchester. His will was published on 9 January 1665 leaving his son John Blachford as his sole heir. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 21 May 1667 found that his widow Mary Blachford and his heir John were seized of, inter alia, the land of Killeclogine alias Killecragan. He had sons John, Thomas, Ambrose and William (who became a Major) and daughters Mary and Frances. Major William Blachford was born in 1658 and died at Lissanover on 28 March 1727. The Blachford family gravestones in Templeport Church read as follows- This monument was erected by MAJOR WILLIAM / BLASHFORD of Lisnover in 1721 to the memory of / his father, JOHN BLASHFORD, late of the same Esqr. but / from Dorchester in Dorsetshire, the place of his / nativity, who in his lifetime chose this for a burying / place, for himself and family, but died in Dublin / was buried in St. Orvins Church but his wife, MARY / RENALD of a Devonsheire family is buried here / as also three sons and two daughters, viz JOHN / AMBROSE AND THOMAS; MARY AND FRANCES / Here likewise lies buried two wives of MAJOR WILLIAM BLASHFORD, son to the said JOHN BLASHFORD viz / MARY MAGHEE of an ancient Family in Lincolnsheire. CORNET CHIDLEY BLACHFORD, son to MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD, leys buried here who dyed August ye 29th, 1722. This aboue MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD. / That erected this monument, died the 28th of March 1727, aged 69 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/memorialspage/Blachford-Memorial-detail.htm |title=Blachford Memorial detail |website=St Peter's Church Templeport  |access-date=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA deed dated 10 May 1744 spells the name as ''Killiclogan''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=78971 | title=Memorial No: 78971 | publisher=Registry of Deeds Index Project Ireland | accessdate=22 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Kilclogan''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf}]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list four tithe payers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killyclugan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killydugan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Killylugan&search=Search],  in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Killycluggin Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1841.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=killycluggin&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 62, being 31 males and 31 females. There were thirteen houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 56, being 29 males and 27 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were twelve houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists sixteen landholders in the townland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191183&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EKillycluggin%3C/b%3E|title=Griffith's Valuation|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 53, being 29 males and 24 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=107;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 36, being 22 males and 14 females. There were nine houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/op1250167-1001]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 53, being 28 males and 25 females. There were nine houses in the townland, all were inhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n295/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 51, being 27 males and 24 females. There were eight houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=296&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there were ten families listed in the townland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Killyclifin/|title=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1901|publisher=}}</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there were only nine families listed in the townland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Killycluggin/|title=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\n# A Neolithic Stone Circle (Site number 62 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated 10m WNW of the site of the celebrated Killycluggin Stone (93). Much disturbed. Subcircular raised area (int. dims. 22m E-W; 18.6m N-S) enclosed by a total of eighteen stones, all but five of which have fallen. The site is divided into two unequal portions by a field boundary running N-S. The smaller portion, W of this, is defined by four orthostats still in position. The largest stone (now fallen) is at NNE (L 3.93m; dims. 1.45m x 0.68m). (\u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in 1979, 155; Killanin and Duignan 1989, 61)''.) <ref>''Antiquities of the Irish Countryside'' by Se\u00e1n P. \u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in (1979), p.55</ref><ref>''The Shell Guide to Ireland'', by Lord Killanin, M.V. Duignan and Peter Harbison (Editor) (1989), p.61.</ref>\n# A La T\u00e8ne decorated standing stone called the [[Killycluggin Stone]] or the [[Crom Cruach]] Stone [http://www.templeport.ie/magh-slecht-dara-fort/plain-of-blood.pd]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} which was originally situated in the above stone circle but is now in [[Cavan County Museum]][http://www.megalithicireland.com/Killycluggin%20Stone,%20Cavan%20Museum.html] [http://www.irishmegaliths.org.uk/zKillycluggin1.htm](Site number 93 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''The Killycluggin stone is a fragmentary decorated monolith of Iron Age date that was first brought to general public notice in 1922 (Macalister 1922). At that time the stone was in the same broken state in which it now appears and was situated some 10m SE of a stone circle (CV013-026002-). Macalister recorded local traditions which alleged that the damage to the stone had been carried out in living memory by local farmers in order to remove an obstruction to agricultural activities. Macalister also stated that people of the vicinity had dug around the stone in a vain search for buried treasure and in so doing had apparently destroyed a 'cist burial'. He did not, however, actually see this 'cist burial'. Some thirty years later a second decorated stone fragment, probably a portion of the same monolith, was discovered a short distance down-slope from the main piece. In the early summer of 1974 it was decided to remove the weathered and overgrown fragments to the National Museum of Ireland. A limited excavation was undertaken in its immediate vicinity which revealed that 'the stone stood in a flat-bottomed pit which had been deliberately sunk 80cm into the subsoil to receive it' (Raftery 1978, 51-2). Immediately E of the stone were two pits one of which may be identified as the remains of the cist burial identified by Macalister as it contained tiny fragments of burnt bone (CV013-026003-). The two fragments of the Killycluggin Stone are on display in the Cavan County Museum, Ballyjamesduff, while a replica stands at the cross-roads c. 250m NW of the original site. The following description of the stone is derived from Raftery (1978, 49-51). The main fragment has been worked to more-or-less cylindrical form on its surviving upper portion. That part which was intended to be below ground level is rough and irregular and projects awkwardly in one direction so that the stone as a whole is crudely L-shaped. The base of the stone slopes obliquely to its vertical axis. The entire upper surface of this stone had been smashed by deliberate and systematic hammering. This destruction continued along one side, whereby the ornament, down to the base of the stone was totally obliterated. The surviving ornament, which comprises combinations of sweeping curves and tight, hair-spring spirals \u2013 classic La T\u00e8ne motifs \u2013 is chiseled deeply and crisply into the prepared surface of the stone. The curvilinear patterns have been divided into rectangular panels by straight vertical lines and by horizontal lines at right angles to them which define the basal extremity of the ornamented area. The precise original width of only one such panel can now be ascertained (c. 0.9m wide and 0.75m high) but it may be estimated that four such panels of decoration once existed on the stone giving an original circumference of 3.6m. The smaller decorated fragment appears to represent a portion of the dome-shaped top of the original monolith and, in this regard, would have resembled that of the best known of the Irish aniconic stones, the stele from Turoe, Co. Galway (GA097-152----). The decoration on this fragment is of two types. Along one edge slight remains of curvilinear patterns, similar to those on the portion just described, survive. Sufficient remains to show that the upper limits of this decoration are defined by a straight line as is the case at the base of the stone, and traces of one of the lines which divide the ornament into vertical, rectangular panels are present here too. The convex upper surface of this fragment is decorated by a series of deeply chiseled, parallel lines which extend across the surface of the stone. The surviving edges of this panel of ornament are defined by a straight line which is incised at an oblique angle to the line which forms the boundary to the zones of curvilinear ornament. Thus there occurs what is now a triangular area, devoid of ornament between the ornament on the apex of the stone and the ornament on the surviving cylindrical part. The two decorated fragments do not join so that neither the original height of the stone nor the precise overall disposition of its ornamentation can now be ascertained. (O\u2019Donovan 1995, no. 93 with further references) The Killycluggin Ornamented stones are subject to a preservation order made under the National Monuments Acts 1930 to 2014 (PO no. 17/1933). References: 1. Macalister, R.A.S. 1922 On a stone with La T\u00e8ne decoration recently discovered in Co. Cavan. Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland 52, 113-16. 2. O'Donovan, P.F. 1995 Archaeological inventory of county Cavan. Dublin. Stationery Office. 3. Raftery, B. 1978 Excavations at Killycluggin, county Cavan. Ulster Journal of Archaeology 41, 49-54.''.) <ref name=\"auto\">''On a Stone with La T\u00e8ne Decoration Recently Discovered in Co. Cavan'', by R. A. S. Macalister, in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Sixth Series, Vol. 12, No. 2 (31 Dec. 1922), pp. 113-116.</ref><ref>''Excavations at Killycluggin, County Cavan'' by Barry Raftery, in Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Third Series, Vol. 41 (1978), pp. 49-54.</ref><ref>''Fragment of the Killycluggin Stone'' by Se\u00e1n P. \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in, in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Vol. 82, No. 1 (1952), p. 68</ref>\n# A [[Bronze Age]] stone cist discovered when excavating the Killycluggin Stone (Site number 165 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995) <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n# A Megalithic Tomb (Site number 46 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''There are three set stones here. A large stone, 1.8m by 0.25m by 1m high, is aligned E-W. To the S and at right angles to its W end is a second stone, 1.25m by 0.25m by 0.4m in exposed height. The third stone, 0.7m W of the S end of the last, is aligned E-W and measures 0.6m by 0.4m by 0.6m high. This configuration of stones may represent the remains of some form of megalithic monument. Field-clearance debris has been heaped around it. (Davies, ITA Survey, Co. Cavan 1941)''.)\n# An earthen ring-fort (Site number 775 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Raised oval area (int. dims. c. 56m NNE-SSW; c. 40m WNW-ESE) enclosed by two substantial earthen banks with wide, deep, partly waterlogged intermediate fosse. From E-S-SW the external bank has been modified and incorporated into the field boundary. From NNW-N-NE the inner bank has been removed and replaced by a modern field boundary. An earlier report (OPW 1969) suggested that the original entrance may have been at WSW. Densely overgrown with vegetation''.)\n# An earthen ring-fort (Site number 774 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- '' Not marked on any OS ed. Raised oval area (int. dims. 35m E-W; 29.2m N-S) divided into two roughly equal portions by the now disused Cavan-Leitrim railway. The portion WNW of this is enclosed by a low much-disturbed bank of earth and stone. Projecting into the internal area from the inner face of the bank at WNW are possible remains of a souterrain (CV013-027002-). The portion ESE of the railway has been largely levelled but its outline is readily identifiable. Original entrance not recognisable''.)\n# An underground [[Souterrain]] discovered in ring-fort No. 774 above (Site number 1244 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated within Killycluggin rath (CV013-027001-). A long, deep depression (L7.7m; Wth 1.8m; D 1m) projecting into the interior from the inner face of the bank of the rath at WNW, may represent a collapsed souterrain''.)\n# A Lime kiln\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.07514|-7.810271|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Killycluggin"}
{"title_page": "Colorado Department of State v. Baca", "text_new": "{{short description|Pending United States Supreme Court case}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Colorado Department of State v. Baca\n  |ArgueDate=\n  |ArgueYear=2020 |DecideDate=\n  |DecideYear=\n  |FullName=\tColorado Department of State, Petitioners v. Micheal Baca, Polly Baca, and Robert Nemanich\n  |USVol=\n  |USPage=\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Docket=19-518 \n  |Prior=''Baca v. Hickenlooper'', [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4549313/baca-v-hickenlooper/ No. 16-cv-02986] (D. Colo.)\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=\n  |NotParticipating=Sotomayor\n  |Majority=\n  |JoinMajority=\n  |Concurrence=\n  |JoinConcurrence=\n  |Concurrence2=\n  |JoinConcurrence2=\n  |Concurrence/Dissent=\n  |JoinConcurrence/Dissent=\n  |Dissent=\n  |JoinDissent=\n  |Dissent2=\n  |JoinDissent2=\n  |LawsApplied=\n}}\n\n'''''Colorado Department of State v. Baca''''', No. 19-518, is a pending case in the 2019-2020 term of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] on the issue of [[faithless elector]]s in the [[United States Electoral College]] stemming from the [[2016 United States Presidential Election]]. The case is based on a challenge to a [[Colorado]] law compelling an elector to vote for the presidential candidate who received the most votes in the state, claiming that electors have discretion to vote as they choose under the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref name=\"Docket 01\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hutchins|first1=Corey|title=Electoral College members file voter 'intimidation' lawsuit against Colorado's secretary of state|url=http://www.coloradoindependent.com/166682/electoral-college-members-file-voter-intimidation-lawsuit-against-colorados-secretary-of-state|publisher=Colorado Independent|date=August 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe case had previously been consolidated with ''[[Chiafalo v. Washington]]'', a similar case concerning faithless electors out of [[Washington (state)|Washington state]]. However, Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]] announced her recusal from the Colorado case due to a prior relationship with one of the respondents, and subsequently the Court separated the cases. Oral arguments had been scheduled for April, but were subsequently postponed due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Background==\n===Faithless electors===\n{{main|Faithless elector}}\nIn the [[United States Electoral College]], faithless electors are those who either cast electoral votes for someone other than the candidate of the party that they pledged to vote for or who [[Abstention|abstain]]. Thirty-two [[U.S. state|state]]s plus the [[District of Columbia]] have passed laws to prevent faithless electors,<ref>{{cite web |title=Faithless Elector State Laws |url=https://www.fairvote.org/faithless_elector_state_laws |website=Fair Vote |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Laws Binding Electors |url=http://presidentialelectorlaws.us |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> but none had been enforced prior to 2016. In 1952, the constitutionality of state pledge laws was brought before the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ray v. Blair]]'', {{ussc|343|214|1952}}. The Court ruled in favor of state laws requiring electors to pledge to vote for the winning candidate in order to be certified as electors, as well as removing electors who refuse to pledge. The court did not rule whether pledges were enforceable. Nevertheless, the court also wrote:\n\n{{quote|However, even if such promises of candidates for the electoral college are legally unenforceable because violative of an ''assumed constitutional freedom of the elector under the Constitution, Art. II, \u00a7 1, to vote as he may choose'' [emphasis added] in the electoral college, it would not follow that the requirement of a pledge in the primary is unconstitutional.}}\n\nIn his dissent, Justice [[Robert H. Jackson]], joined by Justice [[William O. Douglas]], wrote: \"no one faithful to our history can deny that the plan originally contemplated what is implicit in its text \u2013 that electors would be free agents, to exercise an independent and nonpartisan judgment as to the men best qualified for the Nation's highest offices.\"\n\n===Colorado law===\nUnder Colorado law, each presidential elector must vote for the presidential and vice-presidential candidates who received the highest number of votes in Colorado's general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Candidates/FAQs/electoralCollege.html|title=Electoral College FAQs|website=Sos.state.co.us}}</ref>\n\n==Case history==\n{{further|Faithless electors in the United States presidential election, 2016}}\nOn November 8, 2016, while [[Donald Trump]] was declared winner of the 2016 presidential election, his opponent [[Hillary Clinton]] received the most votes in [[United States presidential election in Colorado, 2016|Colorado]], a state allotted 9 electoral votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/63746/183669/Web01/en/summary.html|title=Colorado Election Results|last=Williams|first=Wayne W.|date=November 16, 2016|publisher=Colorado Secretary of State|access-date=November 16, 2016}}</ref> \n\nTwo Democratic electors in the 2016 election sought an [[injunction]] against the state's law after the results of the general election were tallied in early November 2016 but before the electoral college vote on December 19, 2016. The named plaintiff in the case was former Democratic state senator [[Polly Baca]] of Denver, who had indicated she would cast her vote for an alternative Republican candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/presidential-campaign/308255-this-presidential-elector-will-vote-her-conscience|title=This presidential elector will vote her conscience in Electoral College|first=Bill|last=Rehkopf|date=December 1, 2016|website=The Hill|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> The named defendant was [[John Hickenlooper]], then the [[Governor of Colorado]]. They challenged Colorado's law on the basis of their constitutional rights under the Twelfth and [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendments]], as well as the Supreme Court's prior ruling in ''Ray v. Blair'' that left open if states can compel electors to vote as specified with penalties.<ref name=\"denverpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/06/colorado-presidential-electors-lawsuit-to-block-donald-trump/|title=Presidential electors in Colorado file suit to block Donald Trump|first=John |last=Frank|date=December 6, 2016 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]]}}</ref> The electors were part of a grassroots effort to convince other electors to \"vote their conscience for the good of America\" in accordance with [[Alexander Hamilton]]'s [[Federalist No. 68|Federalist Paper No. 68]] and vote for an alternative Republican candidate, even if this were to violate their pledges, to deny Trump a majority in the electoral college and trigger a [[contingent election]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/11/meet-the-hamilton-electors-hoping-for-an-electoral-college-revolt/508433/|title=Meet the 'Hamilton Electors' Campaigning for an Electoral College Revolt|last=O'Donnell|first=Lilly|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hamiltonelectors.com/ |title=Hamilton Electors |newspaper=Hamilton Electors |access-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122235026/http://www.hamiltonelectors.com/ |archivedate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> On December 12, 2016, district judge [[Wiley Daniel]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Colorado]] denied the indicative petition calling the case a \"political stunt.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/12/trump-lawyers-intervene-colorado-lawsuit-free-electors/|title=Judge rejects injunction request in Colorado elector suit seeking to block Donald Trump |website=Denverpost.com}}</ref> \n\nThe elector's appeal of the decision to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit]] was denied on December 16, with the court stating the injunction \"would undermine the electoral process and unduly prejudice the American people by prohibiting a successful transition of power.\u201d The court did not rule on the state's authority to remove an elector after voting, but declared in a footnote that any attempt to remove electors \"after voting has begun\" would be \"unlikely in light of the text of the Twelfth Amendment.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/electors-colorado-court-appeals-232777 |title=Court: Removing 'faithless' electors may be unconstitutional |last=Cheney |first=Kyle |date=December 17, 2016}}</ref> Subsequently, [[Wayne W. Williams|Wayne Williams]], then the [[Secretary of State of Colorado]], stated that he would replace electors who failed to vote for [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\"denverpost.com\" />\n\nWhile both electors ultimately voted for Clinton during the electoral college vote on December 19, a different elector, Micheal <!-- this is the correct spelling according to case documents --> Baca (no relation to Polly), attempted to vote for [[John Kasich]]. Before voting for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]], Williams declared his vote invalid under state law and replaced him with an alternate elector who voted for Clinton and [[Tim Kaine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/19/colorado-electors-new-motion-federal-appeal-denied/ |title = Colorado\u2019s electoral votes go to Hillary Clinton after one is replaced | first=  Brian | last= Eason | date = December 19, 2016 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krdo.com/news/top-stories/one-colorado-elector-fails-to-vote-for-clinton/222689519|title=One Colorado elector fails to vote for Clinton, is replaced|date=20 December 2016|website=Krdo.com}}</ref>\n\nMicheal Baca and the two other electors then filed suit in a new case, ''Nemanich v. Williams'', claiming \"The Constitution does not expressly or implicitly give the states any power to restrict Electors\u2019 freedom beyond the 12th Amendment's single limitation.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Nemanich v Williams Docket 01|url=https://ecf.cod.uscourts.gov/doc1/03917107843|publisher=District of Colorado|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> Later, the respondent was changed to the Colorado Department of State. On April 10, 2018, Judge Daniel granted the motion to dismiss the case on the part of Colorado. The electors appealed to the Tenth Circuit, with oral arguments held in January 2019. Both sides filed a joint motion seeking the court to render a decision on the merits of the case, with Colorado claiming to waive immunity from suit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/07/26/both-sides-in-colorado-disobedient-electors-case-tell-the-tenth-circuit-not-to-duck-the-issue/ |website=Ballot Access News |accessdate=August 21, 2019|title=Both Sides in Colorado \"Disobedient Electors\" Case Tell the Tenth Circuit Not to Duck the Issue &#124; Ballot Access News}}</ref> The court ruled in favor of the electors in a 2-1 vote in August 2019, agreeing that Baca's removal as an elector violated the Twelfth Amendment. The majority opinion, written by circuit judge [[Carolyn Baldwin McHugh]] and joined by circuit judge [[Jerome Holmes]], stated that \"The text of the Constitution makes clear that states do not have the constitutional authority to interfere with presidential electors who exercise their constitutional right to vote for the President and Vice President candidates of their choice.\"<ref name=\"wapost CO 10th\">{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/22/he-tried-stop-trump-electoral-college-court-says-his-faithless-ballot-was-legal/ | title = He tried to stop Trump in the electoral college. A court says his \u2018faithless\u2019 ballot was legal. | first = Meagan | last = Flynn | date = August 22, 2019 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Washington Post]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Colorado Sun |url=https://coloradosun.com/2019/08/21/faithless-electors-court-decision-colorado-10th-circuit/ |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Circuit judge [[Mary Beck Briscoe]] did not take a position on the merits of the case but dissented on [[mootness]] and [[standing (law)|standing]] grounds.<ref name=\"wapost CO 10th\"/> The court did rule that only Micheal <!-- this is the correct spelling according to case documents --> Baca had standing and officially remanded the case back to the district court. The ruling immediately invalidated faithless elector laws in states within the 10th Circuit, specifically in [[New Mexico]], [[Oklahoma]], and [[Wyoming]].\n\n== Supreme Court ==\nInstead of seeking on ''[[en banc]]'' review at the Tenth Circuit,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Derek |title=Does Colorado want to win the state's faithless elector case? |url=https://excessofdemocracy.com/blog/2019/10/does-colorado-want-to-win-the-states-faithless-elector-case |website=Excess of Democracy |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Colorado instead filed a petition for writ of [[certiorari]] to the Supreme Court on October 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colorado asks U.S. Supreme Court to overturn decision allowing presidential electors to vote for whomever they want |url=https://coloradosun.com/2019/10/16/presidential-electors-colorado-supreme-court-micheal-baca/|last=Paul|first=Jesse|date=October 16, 2019 |website=Colorado Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Petition for writ of certiorari |url=https://coag.gov/app/uploads/2019/10/Colorado-Cert-Petition-Final.pdf |website=Colorado Attorney General |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>  Colorado's petition identified the [[circuit split]] between the Tenth's and the [[Washington Supreme Court]] from the prior petition of ''[[Chiafalo v. Washington]]'' (No. 19-465) dealing with a similar matter on faithless electors from Washington state, and seeking the Supreme Court's involvement to resolve the split. Colorado's petition urged for an urgent resolution to the case, as the matter may impact the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.denverpost.com/2019/10/16/colorado-electoral-college-electors-supreme-court/ | title = Colorado seeks \u201curgent\u201d decision from Supreme Court on faithless electors | first = Anna | last = Staver | date = October 16, 2019 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]] }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2020, the Supreme Court agreed to hear the case during the 2019-2020 term, consolidated with ''Chiafalo v. Washington''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/supreme-court/faithless-elector-supreme-court-will-hear-case-could-change-how-n1113051 | title = 'Faithless elector': Supreme Court will hear case that could change how presidents are chosen | first = Pete | last = Williams | date = January 17, 2020 | accessdate = January 17, 2020 | work = [[NBC News]]}}</ref> However, on March 10, Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]] announced that she would recuse herself from the Colorado case, citing her prior friendship with the respondent Polly Baca. As a separate result, the Supreme Court reversed the consolidation of the two cases in a decision that Sotomayor had no part in due to her connection to Baca.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/politics/justice-sotomayor-recuses-from-colorado-faithless-electors-supreme-court-case | title = Justice Sotomayor recuses from Colorado 'faithless electors' Supreme Court case | first =  Blair | last = Miller | date =March 10, 2020 | accessdate = March 10, 2020 | work = [[KMGH-TV]] }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe Supreme Court's decision is highly anticipated with respect to the upcoming [[2020 United States presidential election]]. Though faithless electors have never changed the outcome of an election, some argue the possibility that faithless votes could affect the outcome in a close election increased in light of the events of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/a-nightmare-scenario-for-2020-a-tie-that-cant-be-broken-its-conceivable/2019/10/28/38879e20-f9a6-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html|title=A nightmare scenario for 2020: A tie that can\u2019t be broken. It\u2019s conceivable.|last=Lane|first=Charles|date=2019-10-28|website=The Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n\nThe electors in both cases are represented by [[Lawrence Lessig]], who founded the group [[Equal Citizens]] that is pursuing litigation to seek democratic election reforms and raise awareness. Lessig argued that both cases offered the Supreme Court the opportunity to rule on the matter of faithless elector laws outside the realm of a contested election where their ruling would have a direct impact on the outcome, as in ''[[Bush v. Gore]]''. By clarifying how the Electoral College actually functions, Lessig and Equal Citizens hope to spur Electoral College reform via either a [[Amending the United States Constitution|constitutional amendment]] or the [[National Popular Vote Interstate Compact]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Elector's Freedom |url=https://equalcitizens.us/electors-freedom/ |website=Equal Citizens |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In the latter case, electors from states in the compact combined with electors pledged to the popular vote winner in non-compact states would conceivably create a buffer in electoral votes such that it would take an unprecedented number of faithless electors to threaten the electoral college majority of the popular vote winner.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Docket 01\">{{cite web|title=Nemanich v Williams Docket 01|url=https://ecf.cod.uscourts.gov/doc1/03917107843|publisher=District of Colorado|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:United States One Person, One Vote Legal Doctrine]]\n[[Category:Colorado law]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Stop Trump movement]]\n[[Category:United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit cases]]\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Electoral College (United States)]]\n[[Category:United States Constitution Article Two case law]]\n[[Category:United States elections case law]]\n[[Category:Controversies of the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:John Hickenlooper]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pending United States Supreme Court case}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Colorado Department of State v. Baca\n  |ArgueDate=\n  |ArgueYear=2020 |DecideDate=\n  |DecideYear=\n  |FullName=\tColorado Department of State, Petitioners v. Micheal Baca, Polly Baca, and Robert Nemanich\n  |USVol=\n  |USPage=\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Docket=19-518 \n  |Prior=''Baca v. Hickenlooper'', [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4549313/baca-v-hickenlooper/ No. 16-cv-02986] (D. Colo.)\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=\n  |NotParticipating=Sotomayor\n  |Majority=\n  |JoinMajority=\n  |Concurrence=\n  |JoinConcurrence=\n  |Concurrence2=\n  |JoinConcurrence2=\n  |Concurrence/Dissent=\n  |JoinConcurrence/Dissent=\n  |Dissent=\n  |JoinDissent=\n  |Dissent2=\n  |JoinDissent2=\n  |LawsApplied=\n}}\n\n'''''Colorado Department of State v. Baca''''', No. 19-518, is a pending case in the 2019-2020 term of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] on the issue of [[faithless elector]]s in the [[United States Electoral College]] stemming from the [[2016 United States Presidential Election]]. The case is based on a challenge to a [[Colorado]] law compelling an elector to vote for the presidential candidate who received the most votes in the state, claiming that electors have discretion to vote as they choose under the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref name=\"Docket 01\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hutchins|first1=Corey|title=Electoral College members file voter 'intimidation' lawsuit against Colorado's secretary of state|url=http://www.coloradoindependent.com/166682/electoral-college-members-file-voter-intimidation-lawsuit-against-colorados-secretary-of-state|publisher=Colorado Independent|date=August 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe case had previously been consolidated with ''[[Chiafalo v. Washington]]'', a similar case concerning faithless electors out of [[Washington (state)|Washington state]]. However, Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]] announced her recusal from the Colorado case due to a prior relationship with one of the respondents, and subsequently the Court separated the cases. Oral arguments had been scheduled for April, but were subsequently postponed due to the [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Background==\n===Faithless electors===\n{{main|Faithless elector}}\nIn the [[United States Electoral College]], faithless electors are those who either cast electoral votes for someone other than the candidate of the party that they pledged to vote for or who [[Abstention|abstain]]. Thirty-two [[U.S. state|state]]s plus the [[District of Columbia]] have passed laws to prevent faithless electors,<ref>{{cite web |title=Faithless Elector State Laws |url=https://www.fairvote.org/faithless_elector_state_laws |website=Fair Vote |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Laws Binding Electors |url=http://presidentialelectorlaws.us |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> but none had been enforced prior to 2016. In 1952, the constitutionality of state pledge laws was brought before the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ray v. Blair]]'', {{ussc|343|214|1952}}. The Court ruled in favor of state laws requiring electors to pledge to vote for the winning candidate in order to be certified as electors, as well as removing electors who refuse to pledge. The court did not rule whether pledges were enforceable. Nevertheless, the court also wrote:\n\n{{quote|However, even if such promises of candidates for the electoral college are legally unenforceable because violative of an ''assumed constitutional freedom of the elector under the Constitution, Art. II, \u00a7 1, to vote as he may choose'' [emphasis added] in the electoral college, it would not follow that the requirement of a pledge in the primary is unconstitutional.}}\n\nIn his dissent, Justice [[Robert H. Jackson]], joined by Justice [[William O. Douglas]], wrote: \"no one faithful to our history can deny that the plan originally contemplated what is implicit in its text \u2013 that electors would be free agents, to exercise an independent and nonpartisan judgment as to the men best qualified for the Nation's highest offices.\"\n\n===Colorado law===\nUnder Colorado law, each presidential elector must vote for the presidential and vice-presidential candidates who received the highest number of votes in Colorado's general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Candidates/FAQs/electoralCollege.html|title=Electoral College FAQs|website=Sos.state.co.us}}</ref>\n\n==Case history==\n{{further|Faithless electors in the United States presidential election, 2016}}\nOn November 8, 2016, while [[Donald Trump]] was declared winner of the 2016 presidential election, his opponent [[Hillary Clinton]] received the most votes in [[United States presidential election in Colorado, 2016|Colorado]], a state allotted 9 electoral votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/63746/183669/Web01/en/summary.html|title=Colorado Election Results|last=Williams|first=Wayne W.|date=November 16, 2016|publisher=Colorado Secretary of State|access-date=November 16, 2016}}</ref> \n\nTwo Democratic electors in the 2016 election sought an [[injunction]] against the state's law after the results of the general election were tallied in early November 2016 but before the electoral college vote on December 19, 2016. The named plaintiff in the case was former Democratic state senator [[Polly Baca]] of Denver, who had indicated she would cast her vote for an alternative Republican candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/presidential-campaign/308255-this-presidential-elector-will-vote-her-conscience|title=This presidential elector will vote her conscience in Electoral College|first=Bill|last=Rehkopf|date=December 1, 2016|website=The Hill|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> The named defendant was [[John Hickenlooper]], then the [[Governor of Colorado]]. They challenged Colorado's law on the basis of their constitutional rights under the Twelfth and [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendments]], as well as the Supreme Court's prior ruling in ''Ray v. Blair'' that left open if states can compel electors to vote as specified with penalties.<ref name=\"denverpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/06/colorado-presidential-electors-lawsuit-to-block-donald-trump/|title=Presidential electors in Colorado file suit to block Donald Trump|first=John |last=Frank|date=December 6, 2016 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]]}}</ref> The electors were part of a grassroots effort to convince other electors to \"vote their conscience for the good of America\" in accordance with [[Alexander Hamilton]]'s [[Federalist No. 68|Federalist Paper No. 68]] and vote for an alternative Republican candidate, even if this were to violate their pledges, to deny Trump a majority in the electoral college and trigger a [[contingent election]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/11/meet-the-hamilton-electors-hoping-for-an-electoral-college-revolt/508433/|title=Meet the 'Hamilton Electors' Campaigning for an Electoral College Revolt|last=O'Donnell|first=Lilly|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hamiltonelectors.com/ |title=Hamilton Electors |newspaper=Hamilton Electors |access-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122235026/http://www.hamiltonelectors.com/ |archivedate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> On December 12, 2016, district judge [[Wiley Daniel]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Colorado]] denied the indicative petition calling the case a \"political stunt.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/12/trump-lawyers-intervene-colorado-lawsuit-free-electors/|title=Judge rejects injunction request in Colorado elector suit seeking to block Donald Trump |website=Denverpost.com}}</ref> \n\nThe elector's appeal of the decision to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit]] was denied on December 16, with the court stating the injunction \"would undermine the electoral process and unduly prejudice the American people by prohibiting a successful transition of power.\u201d The court did not rule on the state's authority to remove an elector after voting, but declared in a footnote that any attempt to remove electors \"after voting has begun\" would be \"unlikely in light of the text of the Twelfth Amendment.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/electors-colorado-court-appeals-232777 |title=Court: Removing 'faithless' electors may be unconstitutional |last=Cheney |first=Kyle |date=December 17, 2016}}</ref> Subsequently, [[Wayne W. Williams|Wayne Williams]], then the [[Secretary of State of Colorado]], stated that he would replace electors who failed to vote for [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\"denverpost.com\" />\n\nWhile both electors ultimately voted for Clinton during the electoral college vote on December 19, a different elector, Micheal <!-- this is the correct spelling according to case documents --> Baca (no relation to Polly), attempted to vote for [[John Kasich]]. Before voting for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]], Williams declared his vote invalid under state law and replaced him with an alternate elector who voted for Clinton and [[Tim Kaine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/19/colorado-electors-new-motion-federal-appeal-denied/ |title = Colorado\u2019s electoral votes go to Hillary Clinton after one is replaced | first=  Brian | last= Eason | date = December 19, 2016 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krdo.com/news/top-stories/one-colorado-elector-fails-to-vote-for-clinton/222689519|title=One Colorado elector fails to vote for Clinton, is replaced|date=20 December 2016|website=Krdo.com}}</ref>\n\nMicheal Baca and the two other electors then filed suit in a new case, ''Nemanich v. Williams'', claiming \"The Constitution does not expressly or implicitly give the states any power to restrict Electors\u2019 freedom beyond the 12th Amendment's single limitation.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Nemanich v Williams Docket 01|url=https://ecf.cod.uscourts.gov/doc1/03917107843|publisher=District of Colorado|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> Later, the respondent was changed to the Colorado Department of State. On April 10, 2018, Judge Daniel granted the motion to dismiss the case on the part of Colorado. The electors appealed to the Tenth Circuit, with oral arguments held in January 2019. Both sides filed a joint motion seeking the court to render a decision on the merits of the case, with Colorado claiming to waive immunity from suit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/07/26/both-sides-in-colorado-disobedient-electors-case-tell-the-tenth-circuit-not-to-duck-the-issue/ |website=Ballot Access News |accessdate=August 21, 2019|title=Both Sides in Colorado \"Disobedient Electors\" Case Tell the Tenth Circuit Not to Duck the Issue &#124; Ballot Access News}}</ref> The court ruled in favor of the electors in a 2-1 vote in August 2019, agreeing that Baca's removal as an elector violated the Twelfth Amendment. The majority opinion, written by circuit judge [[Carolyn Baldwin McHugh]] and joined by circuit judge [[Jerome Holmes]], stated that \"The text of the Constitution makes clear that states do not have the constitutional authority to interfere with presidential electors who exercise their constitutional right to vote for the President and Vice President candidates of their choice.\"<ref name=\"wapost CO 10th\">{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/22/he-tried-stop-trump-electoral-college-court-says-his-faithless-ballot-was-legal/ | title = He tried to stop Trump in the electoral college. A court says his \u2018faithless\u2019 ballot was legal. | first = Meagan | last = Flynn | date = August 22, 2019 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Washington Post]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Colorado Sun |url=https://coloradosun.com/2019/08/21/faithless-electors-court-decision-colorado-10th-circuit/ |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Circuit judge [[Mary Beck Briscoe]] did not take a position on the merits of the case but dissented on [[mootness]] and [[standing (law)|standing]] grounds.<ref name=\"wapost CO 10th\"/> The court did rule that only Micheal <!-- this is the correct spelling according to case documents --> Baca had standing and officially remanded the case back to the district court. The ruling immediately invalidated faithless elector laws in states within the 10th Circuit, specifically in [[New Mexico]], [[Oklahoma]], and [[Wyoming]].\n\n== Supreme Court ==\nInstead of seeking on ''[[en banc]]'' review at the Tenth Circuit,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Derek |title=Does Colorado want to win the state's faithless elector case? |url=https://excessofdemocracy.com/blog/2019/10/does-colorado-want-to-win-the-states-faithless-elector-case |website=Excess of Democracy |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Colorado instead filed a petition for writ of [[certiorari]] to the Supreme Court on October 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colorado asks U.S. Supreme Court to overturn decision allowing presidential electors to vote for whomever they want |url=https://coloradosun.com/2019/10/16/presidential-electors-colorado-supreme-court-micheal-baca/|last=Paul|first=Jesse|date=October 16, 2019 |website=Colorado Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Petition for writ of certiorari |url=https://coag.gov/app/uploads/2019/10/Colorado-Cert-Petition-Final.pdf |website=Colorado Attorney General |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>  Colorado's petition identified the [[circuit split]] between the Tenth's and the [[Washington Supreme Court]] from the prior petition of ''[[Chiafalo v. Washington]]'' (No. 19-465) dealing with a similar matter on faithless electors from Washington state, and seeking the Supreme Court's involvement to resolve the split. Colorado's petition urged for an urgent resolution to the case, as the matter may impact the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.denverpost.com/2019/10/16/colorado-electoral-college-electors-supreme-court/ | title = Colorado seeks \u201curgent\u201d decision from Supreme Court on faithless electors | first = Anna | last = Staver | date = October 16, 2019 | accessdate = February 26, 2020 | work = [[The Denver Post]] }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2020, the Supreme Court agreed to hear the case during the 2019-2020 term, consolidated with ''Chiafalo v. Washington''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/supreme-court/faithless-elector-supreme-court-will-hear-case-could-change-how-n1113051 | title = 'Faithless elector': Supreme Court will hear case that could change how presidents are chosen | first = Pete | last = Williams | date = January 17, 2020 | accessdate = January 17, 2020 | work = [[NBC News]]}}</ref> However, on March 10, Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]] announced that she would recuse herself from the Colorado case, citing her prior friendship with the respondent Polly Baca. As a separate result, the Supreme Court reversed the consolidation of the two cases in a decision that Sotomayor had no part in due to her connection to Baca.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/politics/justice-sotomayor-recuses-from-colorado-faithless-electors-supreme-court-case | title = Justice Sotomayor recuses from Colorado 'faithless electors' Supreme Court case | first =  Blair | last = Miller | date =March 10, 2020 | accessdate = March 10, 2020 | work = [[KMGH-TV]] }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe Supreme Court's decision is highly anticipated with respect to the upcoming [[2020 United States presidential election]]. Though faithless electors have never changed the outcome of an election, some argue the possibility that faithless votes could affect the outcome in a close election increased in light of the events of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/a-nightmare-scenario-for-2020-a-tie-that-cant-be-broken-its-conceivable/2019/10/28/38879e20-f9a6-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html|title=A nightmare scenario for 2020: A tie that can\u2019t be broken. It\u2019s conceivable.|last=Lane|first=Charles|date=2019-10-28|website=The Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n\nThe electors in both cases are represented by [[Lawrence Lessig]], who founded the group [[Equal Citizens]] that is pursuing litigation to seek democratic election reforms and raise awareness. Lessig argued that both cases offered the Supreme Court the opportunity to rule on the matter of faithless elector laws outside the realm of a contested election where their ruling would have a direct impact on the outcome, as in ''[[Bush v. Gore]]''. By clarifying how the Electoral College actually functions, Lessig and Equal Citizens hope to spur Electoral College reform via either a [[Amending the United States Constitution|constitutional amendment]] or the [[National Popular Vote Interstate Compact]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Elector's Freedom |url=https://equalcitizens.us/electors-freedom/ |website=Equal Citizens |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In the latter case, electors from states in the compact combined with electors pledged to the popular vote winner in non-compact states would conceivably create a buffer in electoral votes such that it would take an unprecedented number of faithless electors to threaten the electoral college majority of the popular vote winner.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Docket 01\">{{cite web|title=Nemanich v Williams Docket 01|url=https://ecf.cod.uscourts.gov/doc1/03917107843|publisher=District of Colorado|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:United States One Person, One Vote Legal Doctrine]]\n[[Category:Colorado law]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Stop Trump movement]]\n[[Category:United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit cases]]\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Electoral College (United States)]]\n[[Category:United States Constitution Article Two case law]]\n[[Category:United States elections case law]]\n[[Category:Controversies of the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:John Hickenlooper]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n", "name_user": "Mdewman6", "label": "safe", "comment": "better link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colorado_Department_of_State_v._Baca"}
{"title_page": "Joyful Noise Recordings", "text_new": "{{short description|American independent record label from Indianapolis, Indiana}}\n{{Other uses|Joyful Noise (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = Joyful Noise\n| image       = Joyful Noise logo.png\n| founded     = {{start date|2003}}\n| founder     = Karl Hofstetter\n| distributor = [[Secretly Canadian]]\n| genre       = [[Indie rock]], [[alternative rock]], [[experimental music|experimental]], [[doom metal]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n| url         = {{URL|www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Joyful Noise Recordings''' is an [[independent record label]] from [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]. The label was founded in [[2003 in music|2003]] in [[Bloomington, Indiana]] by Karl Hofstetter, who also played drums on many of the label's first releases.<ref name=officialcontact>{{cite web|url=http://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/contact |title=About / Contact - Joyful Noise Recordings |publisher=JoyfulNoiseRecordings.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref> Joyful Noise currently has a roster of 20+ bands of various musical styles, though according to the label, each artist \"in one way or another bridges this gap between [[pop music|pop]] and [[noise music|noise]].\"<ref name=officialcontact/> Along with housing offices and the warehouse of the label, their [[Fountain Square, Indianapolis|Fountain Square]] location hosts live shows and a small record store.\n\nIn [[2010 in music|2010]] Joyful Noise began focusing largely on limited edition specialty releases which are generally released on [[Analog recording|analog]] formats packaged with [[music downloads]]. In addition to releases on [[vinyl records]], the label has gained notoriety for being at the forefront of the resurgence of [[cassette tapes]] and [[flexidisc|flexi-discs]], as reported by [[The Washington Post]], [[Pitchfork Media]], [[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under The Radar]], and others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Coplen|first=Katherine|title=2013 Cultural Vision Awards: Joyful Noise Recordings|url=http://www.nuvo.net/indianapolis/2013-cvas-joyful-noise-recordings/Content?oid=2605192|publisher=NUVO|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lindquist|first=David|title=Dinosaur Jr. cassette tape helped push local label onto national scene|url=http://www.indystar.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2013310060062&nclick_check=1|accessdate=5 November 2013|newspaper=Indianapolis Star|date=October 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Curran|first=Katie|title=Cassette tapes make a comeback|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2011-05-21/lifestyle/35232396_1_cassette-tapes-animal-collective-deerhoof|accessdate=5 November 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=May 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Laban|first=Linda|title=Still stuck on tapes|url=https://nypost.com/2011/09/18/still-stuck-on-tapes/|accessdate=5 November 2013|newspaper=New York Post|date=September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|title=Of Montreal, Tortoise, Akron/Family, Deerhoof on Joyful Noise Flexi Series|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/44975-of-montreal-tortoise-akronfamily-deerhoof-on-joyful-noise-flexi-series/|accessdate=5 November 2013|newspaper=Pitchfork|date=January 4, 2012}}</ref>\n \nJoyful Noise has released single-album cassettes from [[Akron/Family]], [[Dinosaur Jr.]], [[Deerhoof]], [[of Montreal]], [[Here We Go Magic]], and others, and has released multi-album Cassette Box Sets from Dinosaur Jr., of Montreal, and [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan Of Arc]].<ref name=officialcontact/>\n\nIn 2012 Joyful Noise released their first album to chart on Billboard: [[Kishi Bashi]] \"151a\" (debuting at #6 on the \"Heatseekers\" chart).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/|title=Billboard - Music Charts, News, Photos & Video|author=|date=|website=billboard.com|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> Since that time, new music on Joyful Noise from artists such as [[Sebadoh]], [[Dumb Numbers]], [[David Yow]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Furry|first=Jeanne|title=Former Jesus Lizard David Yow Casts Lewd, Clanging Solo Album Debut|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1565551/former-jesus-lizard-david-yow-casts-lewd-clanging-solo-album-debut|publisher=Billboard Magazine|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref> and [[Son Lux]] have all charted.\n\n==Bands==\n\n=== Current roster ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Big Business (band)|Big Business]]\n* Busman's Holiday\n* CJ Boyd\n* Crosss\n* [[Dale Crover]]\n* [[David Yow]]\n* [[Deerhoof]]\n* [[Divorcee]]\n* [[Dumb Numbers]] \n* Eerie Wanda\n* [[Goblin Cock]]\n* [[Half Japanese]]\n* [[Helvetia (band)|Helvetia]]\n* [[Dale Crover|Hew Time]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n* J Fernandez\n* [[Jad Fair]]\n* [[Jason Loewenstein]]\n* [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan of Arc]]\n* [[Kishi Bashi]]\n* KO\n* [[Lil Bub]]\n* [[Lou Barlow]]\n* [[The Low Anthem]]\n* Memory Map\n* [[Mike Adams At His Honest Weight]]\n* [[Mythless]]\n* No Joy/Sonic Boom\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[OHMME]]\n* [[Oneida (band)|Oneida]]\n* [[The Ophelias (Ohio band)|The Ophelias]]\n* Psychic Temple\n* [[Rafter (band)|Rafter]]\n* [[Reptar (band)|Reptar]]\n* [[Margot & the Nuclear So and So's|Richard Edwards]]\n* Sedcairne Archives\n* [[Serengeti (rapper)|Serengeti]]\n* [[Sisyphus]]\n* [[Sleep Party People]]\n* Solos\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Son Lux]]\n* [[Sound of Ceres]]\n* [[Stranger Cat]]\n* [[Surfer Blood]]\n* [[Swamp Dogg]]\n* Tall Tall Trees\n* [[Tim Kinsella]]\n* [[Victor Villareal (musician)|Victor Villarreal]]\n* [[Why? (American band)|WHY?]]\n* [[Yonatan Gat]]\n* Yoni & Geti\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== \"Open Relationships\" ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Akron/Family]]\n*[[Anal Trump]]\n*[[Ava Luna]]\n*[[Nate Kinsella|Birthmark]]\n*[[Born Ruffians]]\n* Brian Marella\n*[[Built to Spill]]\n* Childbite\n*[[Chris Cohen (musician)|Chris Cohen]]\n*[[Cloud Nothings]]\n*[[Daniel Johnston]]\n*[[Danielson]]\n*[[David Lynch]]\n*[[Dead Rider]]\n*[[Dinosaur Jr.]] \n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Divorc\u00e9e\n*[[DM Stith]]\n* DMA\n*[[Don Caballero]]\n*[[Eric Gaffney]]\n*[[Fang Island]]\n* Father Murphy\n*[[Godspeed You! Black Emperor]]\n*[[Hella (band)|Hella]]\n*[[Here We Go Magic]]\n* Jad Fair & Norman Blake\n*[[Japandroids]]\n* The Jesus Lizard\n* Jorma Whittaker\n*[[Julianna Barwick]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Buzz Osborne|King Buzzo]]\n* KO\n*[[Le Butcherettes]]\n*[[Lee Ranaldo]]\n*[[Make Believe (band)|Make Believe]]\n*[[Marmoset (band)|Marmoset]]\n*[[Marnie Stern]]\n*[[Melvins]]\n*[[Monotonix]]\n*[[Mount Eerie]]\n* Natural Dreamers\n*[[Of Montreal]]\n*[[Ought (band)|Ought]]\n*[[Owls (band)|Owls]]\n* Pattern is Movement\n* [[Prince Rama]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Protomartyr (band)|Protomartyr]]\n*[[Qui (band)|Qui]]\n*[[Racebannon]]\n*[[Richard Swift (singer-songwriter)|Richard Swift]]\n*[[Rob Crow]]\n*[[The Sea and Cake]]\n* S.M. Wolf\n* Solos\n*[[Son Lux]]\n* Sonny & The Sunsets\n*[[Sondre Lerche]]\n*[[Sufjan Stevens]]\n* Swaps\n* Swirlies\n*[[Talk Normal]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}} \n*[[Tera Melos]]\n*[[Thee Oh Sees]]\n* Thom Fekete\n*[[Thurston Moore]]\n*[[Tortoise (band)|Tortoise]]\n* The Unspeakable Practices\n*[[Wye Oak]]\n* Yip Deceiver\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Past roster ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Abner Trio\n* Berry\n* Big Bear\n* Bizzart\n* The Delicious\n* [[Grampall Jookabox]]\n* Hermit Thrushes\n* Hi Red Center\n* [[I Love You (Yah Tibyah La Blu)]]\n* [[Jookabox]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Lafcadio\n* Man at Arms\n* Manners for Husbands\n* Melk the g6-49\n* Prizzy Prizzy Please\n* Push-Pull\n* Receptor Sight\n* [[Sebadoh]]\n* [[Stationary Odyssey]]\n* [[Valina]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Subscriptions and series==\n\n===Artist in Residence===\nStarting in 2014, Joyful Noise began hosting artists for year-long residencies in which they release new music exclusively on the label. \n*[[Thor Harris]] 2019<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6>{{cite web |publisher=Joyful Noise Recordings |title=Thor Harris: 2019 Artist in Residence |date=2019 |url=https://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/collections/new-releases/products/2019-artist-in-residence |accessdate=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n*[[Rob Crow]] 2018\n*[[Deerhoof]] 2017\n*[[Tim Kinsella]] 2015\n*[[Jad Fair]] 2014\n\n===Flexi Disc Series===\nIn late 2011 Joyful Noise announced their [http://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/catalog/jnr100 2012 Flexi Disc Series], which featured singles from [[Deerhoof]], [[Jad Fair]], [[Lou Barlow]], [[of Montreal]], and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/44975-of-montreal-tortoise-akronfamily-deerhoof-on-joyful-noise-flexi-series/ |title=Of Montreal, Tortoise, Akron/Family, Deerhoof on Joyful Noise Flexi Series &#124; News |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref> Each artist contributed a single song which is not available anywhere else. Each [[Flexi disc|Flexi Disc]] was limited to 500 copies, and were sold as a monthly subscription. Now in its fourth year, the Flexi Disc series has upped their distribution to 1000 copies of each single and grown to include acts such as [[Cloud Nothings]], [[Sonny Smith (musician)|Sonny & the Sunsets]], [[Lee Ranaldo]], [[Thurston Moore]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/collections/flexi-disc-series |title=Flexi Disc Series! |publisher=JoyfulNoiseRecordings.com |date=2015-06-08 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n====2015 Artists====\n*[[Arousal (band)|Arousal]]\n*[[Cloud Nothings]]\n*[[Deerhoof]] and [[Celestial Shore]]\n*[[Goblin Cock]]\n*[[King Buzzo]]\n*[[Lee Ranaldo]]\n*[[Oneida (band)|Oneida]]\n*[[Pattern is Movement]]\n*[[Protomartyr (band)|Protomartyr]]\n*[[Sonny Smith (musician)|Sonny & the Sunsets]]\n*[[Tera Melos]]\n*[[Wye Oak (band)|Wye Oak]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n====2014 