ince 1971)\n|1896\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Geordie Greig]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Daily Mail and General Trust plc]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Right-wing]], [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]]\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|-\n|''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''\n|Sundays\n|Tabloid\n|1982\n|-\n|''[[Daily Express]]''\n|Daily\n|Broadsheet (1900 \u2013 1977)\nTabloid (since 1978)\n|1900\n|[[Gary Jones (journalist)|Gary Jones]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Trinity Mirror|Reach]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Right-wing]], [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]]\n|-\n|''[[Sunday Express]]''\n|Sundays\n|Broadsheet (1918 \u2013 1992)\nTabloid (since 1992)\n|1918\n|Michael Booker\n|-\n| ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' || Daily || Tabloid || 1964 \n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Tony Gallagher]]|| rowspan=\"2\" |[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Right-wing]], [[conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Sun on Sunday]]'' || Sundays || Tabloid || 2012 \n|-\n| ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' || Daily || Tabloid || 1903 \n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Lloyd Embley]]|| rowspan=\"5\" |[[Trinity Mirror|Reach]] ||rowspan=\"3\"| [[Centre-left]] ||rowspan=\"3\"| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' || Sundays || Tabloid || 1915\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday People]]'' || Sundays || Tabloid || 1881 \n|Peter Willis\n|-\n| ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]''  || Daily || Tabloid || 1978 \n|[[Dawn Neesom]]|| rowspan=\"2\" | Largely non-political ||rowspan=\"2\" |None\n|-\n| ''[[Daily Star Sunday]]'' || Sundays || Tabloid || 2002 \n|[[Stuart James]]\n|-\n| ''[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]'' || Daily || Tabloid || 1930 \n|[[Ben Chacko]]||[[People's Press Printing Society]]||[[Left-wing]], [[socialism|socialist]] || [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|-\n|''[[Eastern Eye]]''\n|Weekly\n|Tabloid\n|1989\n|\n|Asian Media Group\n|\n|None\n|}\n\n==Freesheet newspapers in urban centres==\n\n:{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Title\n!Days of Publication\n!  style=\" text-align:center;\"| Format\n!  style=\"text-align:center;\"| Established\n!Editor\n! Owner\n! Political<br>Orientation\n! Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' || Weekdays (evening) || Tabloid || 1827 \n|[[George Osborne]]||[[Alexander Lebedev]] (75.1%)<br />[[Lord Rothermere]] (24.9%) ||[[Centre-right]], [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]] || [[Greater London]]\n|-\n| ''[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]]'' || Weekdays|| Tabloid || 1999 \n|[[Ted Young (journalist)|Ted Young]]||[[Daily Mail and General Trust plc]] ||[[Nonpartisanism|Non-partisan]], neutral\n| Wide availability in the major cities\n|-\n| ''[[City A.M.]]'' || Weekdays (morning)|| Tabloid || 2005 \n|Christian May|| City A.M. Ltd ||  [[Centre-right]], [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]] || Wide availability in the major cities\n|-\n| ''[[The Shuttle (newspaper)|The Shuttle]]'' || Weekly|| Tabloid || 1870 \n|Peter John|| Newsquest Media Group ||Local politics\n|[[Wyre Forest]] area of [[Worcestershire]]\n|-\n\n|''Asian Express''\n|Weekly\n|Tabloid\n|1999\n|\n|Media Buzz Ltd\n\n|\n|-\n| ''Yorkshire Reporter'' || Monthly|| Tabloid || 2013 \n| || Pick up Publications Ltd ||  || Widely available in Leeds and its surrounding areas\n|}\n\n===Magazines===\nA large range of [[magazine]]s are sold in the United Kingdom covering most interests and potential topics. British magazines and journals that have achieved worldwide circulation include ''[[The Economist]]'', ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'', and ''[[New Scientist]]'',  ''[[Private Eye]]'', ''[[Hello!]]'', ''[[The Spectator]]'', the ''[[Radio Times]]'', and ''[[NME]]''.\n\n===Books===\n{{main|Books in the United Kingdom}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\n===Radio===\n[[File:Truetone-Radio.jpg|thumb|Picture of a Truetone brand radio]]\n{{Main|Radio in the United Kingdom|Digital radio in the United Kingdom}}\nRadio in the United Kingdom is dominated by the BBC, which operates [[BBC Radio|radio]] stations both in the United Kingdom and abroad. The [[BBC World Service]] radio network is broadcast in 33 languages globally. Domestically the BBC also operates ten national networks and over 40 local radio stations including services in Welsh on [[BBC Radio Cymru]], Gaelic on [[BBC Radio nan G\u00e0idheal]] in Scotland and Irish in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/languages/index.shtml |title=News and Analysis in your language |publisher=BBC |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref> The domestic services of the BBC are funded by the [[television licence]].<ref name=\"TV Licence Fee: facts & figures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/keyfacts/stories/licencefee.shtml |title=TV Licence Fee: facts & figures |publisher=BBC Press Office |accessdate=30 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907023331/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/keyfacts/stories/licencefee.shtml |archivedate=7 September 2010 }}</ref> The internationally targeted BBC World Service Radio is funded by the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], though from 2014 it will be funded by the television licence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofcomwatch.co.uk/2010/10/bbc-funding-settlement-the-details/ |title=BBC Funding Settlements: the details |publisher=OFCOMWATCH |date=October 2010 |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref> The most popular radio station by number of listeners is [[BBC Radio 2]], closely followed by [[BBC Radio 4]]. Advances in [[Digital audio broadcast|digital radio]] technology have enabled the launch of several new stations by the Corporation.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2573045.stm \"BBC7 radio launches with comedy\"], ''BBC News'', 16 December 2002, retrieved 10 July 2011.</ref>\n\nRather than operating as independent entities, many commercial local radio stations are owned by large radio groups which broadcast a similar format to many areas. The largest operator of radio stations is [[Global Radio]], owner of the major [[Heart Network|Heart]], [[Smooth Radio|Smooth]] and [[Capital (radio network)|Capital]] radio brands. It also owns [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]], [[LBC]] and [[Radio X (United Kingdom)|Radio X]]. Other owners are [[Wireless Group]] and [[Bauer Radio]]. There are a number of licensed [[Radio in the United Kingdom#Community radio|community radio]] stations<ref>[http://a-bc.co.uk/community-radio-station-map/ Map of Community radio stations broadcasting in the UK]</ref> which broadcast to local audiences.\n\n===Television===\n{{Main|Television in the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:Channel 4 Building - Horseferry Road - London - 310504.jpg|thumb|The [[Channel 4]] building in London]]\nThe United Kingdom has no analogue [[television]]. A free to air digital service is made up of two [[Public broadcasting|chartered]] public broadcasting companies, the [[BBC]] and [[Channel 4]] and two franchised commercial television companies, ([[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]). In addition to this, the United Kingdom's free-to-air [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] service runs a large number of Entertainment, Music, Sport and Shopping channels from the likes of [[CBS]], [[UKTV]] and [[Sky UK|Sky]]. There are five major nationwide [[Television in the United Kingdom|television channels]]: [[BBC One]], [[BBC Two]], [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]], [[Channel 4]] and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]\u2014currently transmitted by digital terrestrial, free-to-air signals with the latter three channels funded by commercial advertising. The vast majority of digital cable television services are provided by [[Virgin Media]] with satellite television available from [[Freesat]] or [[Sky UK|Sky]] and [[free-to-air]] digital terrestrial television by [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]]. The entire country [[Digit Al|switched to digital]] (from a previously analogue signal) in 2012.<ref name=\"What is digital switchover\">{{cite web |url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/en/HomeAndCommunity/TechnologyInYourHome/DigitalTelevision/DG_10031292 |title=What is digital switchover |publisher=Directgov |date=December 2010 |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] operates several [[BBC Television|television channels]] in the United Kingdom and abroad. The BBC's international television news service, [[BBC World News]], is broadcast throughout the world. The domestic services of the BBC are funded by the [[television licence]].<ref name=\"TV Licence Fee: facts & figures\"/> The international television broadcast services are operated by [[BBC Worldwide]] on a commercial subscription basis over cable and satellite services. This commercial arm of the BBC also forms half of [[UKTV]] along with [[Virgin Media]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcworldwide.com/channels.aspx |title=CHANNELS |publisher=BBC Worldwide |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nChannel 4 is similarly chartered to the BBC, with a remit to provide public service broadcasting and schools programs, however it runs commercial [[advertisement]]s to provide a revenue stream. It produces a number of digital channels, branded as [[Channel 4]], as well as [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]], [[More 4]] and [[Film4]].\n\nThe commercial operators rely on advertising for their revenue, and are run as commercial ventures, in contrast to the public service operators. The [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] franchise transmits the 3 different networks in different parts of the country. These are known as [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] (in England, Wales, Scottish Borders, Isle of Man and [[Channel Television|Channel Islands]]), [[STV (TV network)|STV]] (In Central and Northern Scotland), and [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] in Northern Ireland.\n\n==Internet==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{Main|Internet in the United Kingdom}}\n\nThe United Kingdom's most visited websites include google.com, youtube.co.uk, facebook.com, bbc.co.uk, google.co.uk, and ebay.co.uk.<ref>https://www.similarweb.com/top-websites/united-kingdom</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alternative media in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Criticism of the BBC]]\n*[[List of television stations in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Media of Northern Ireland]]\n*[[Media of Scotland]]\n*[[Media of Wales]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|editor1=Euromedia Research Group |editor2=Mary Kelly|display-editors=etal|title= Media in Europe |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_KRfXsBUBeAC|publisher=[[Sage Publications]] |isbn=978-0-7619-4132-3 |edition=3rd |year=2004\n|chapter= United Kingdom\n|pages= \n}}\n* {{cite book |first      = Alison\n |last       = Harcourt\n |title      = European Union Institutions and the Regulation of Media Markets\n |edition    = \n |publisher  = Manchester University Press\n |location   = [[London]], [[New York City]]\n |year       = 2006\n |id         = \n |url        = https://archive.org/details/europeanunionreg0000harc\n |isbn       = 0-7190-6644-1\n |url-access = registration\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://uk.allmedialink.com United Kingdom's All Newspapers & Media]. United Kingdom's Newspapers and other types of media from the UK.\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/oct/21/uk-media-plurality-threatened-by-dominant-group-of-large-firms-report UK media plurality threatened by a dominant group of large firms \u2013 report]. ''The Guardian''. Published 21 October 2015. Retrieved 7 December 2017.\n\n{{Media in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Europe topic|Media of}}\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n{{Economy of the United Kingdom}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Europe topic|Media of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media Of The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Media in the United Kingdom| ]]\n", "text_old": "There are several different types of media in the [[United Kingdom]]: television, radio, newspapers, magazines and websites. The country also has a strong [[Music of the United Kingdom|music industry]]. The United Kingdom has a diverse range of providers, the most prominent being the publicly owned [[public service broadcaster]], the British Broadcasting Corporation ([[BBC]]). The BBC's largest competitors are [[ITV plc]], which operates 13 of the 15 regional television broadcasters that make up the ITV Network, and American global media conglomerate [[Comcast]], which owns the broadcaster [[Sky Limited|Sky Ltd]]. Regional media is covered by local radio, television and print newspapers. [[Trinity Mirror]] operates 240 local and regional newspapers, as well as national newspapers such as the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' and the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]''.\n\n==Audiences==\n[[File:Salford quays swing bridge.jpg|thumb|right|[[MediaCityUK|Mediacity]] in [[Greater Manchester]], privately funded and publicly backed by the BBC is the largest media-production facility in the United Kingdom.]]\nIn 2009 it was estimated that individuals viewed a mean of 3.75 hours of television per day and listened to 2.81 hours of radio. The main BBC [[Public service broadcasting in the United Kingdom|public service broadcasting]] channels accounted for and estimated 28.4% of all television viewing; the three main independent channels accounted for 29.5% and the increasingly important other satellite and digital channels for the remaining 42.1%.<ref>[[Ofcom]] [http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/cmr/753567/CMR_2010_FINAL.pdf \"Communication Market Report 2010\"], 19 August 2010, pp. 97, 164 and 191, retrieved 17 June 2011.</ref> Sales of newspapers have fallen since the 1970s and in 2009 42% of people reported reading a daily national newspaper.<ref>{{Citation|title=Social Trends: Lifestyles and social participation |journal=Office for National Statistics |date=16 February 2010 |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/cci/nugget.asp?id=2356 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624060145/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/cci/nugget.asp?id=2356 |archivedate=24 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref> In 2010, 82.5% of the United Kingdom population were Internet users, the highest proportion amongst the 20 countries with the largest total number of users in that year.<ref>{{Citation|title=Top 20 countries with the highest number of Internet users |journal=Internet World Stats |url=http://www.internetworldstats.com/top20.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610104435/http://www.internetworldstats.com/top20.htm |archivedate=10 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[European Broadcasting Union]] research found that people in the United Kingdom trusted the written press least of any European country, by a considerable margin. Trust in television and the radio was closer to the European average.<ref name=pg-20170526>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/survey-finds-that-uk-written-press-is-by-some-way-the-least-trusted-in-europe/ |title=Survey finds that UK written press is (by some way) the least trusted in Europe |last=Ponsford |first=Dominic |work=Press Gazette |date=26 May 2017 |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==National media centres and organisations==\n\n===London===\n{{Main|Media in London}}\nLondon dominates the media sector in the United Kingdom as national newspapers, television and radio networks are largely based there. Notable centres include [[Fleet Street]] and [[BBC Broadcasting House]].\n\nSpecialist local paper [[City A.M.]] is a free, business-focused newspaper published in print Monday to Friday. It is typically available from around 6{{nbsp}}am at London commuter stations and is handed out at key points in the City, Canary Wharf and other central London locations.\n\n===Greater Manchester===\n{{Main|Media in Manchester}}\nGreater Manchester is also a significant national media hub. Notable centres include [[MediaCityUK]] a 200-acre (80ha) media production facility in [[City of Salford|Salford]] and [[Trafford]].\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' national newspaper was founded in Manchester in 1821, and was known as the ''Manchester Guardian'' until 1959. In the 1950s, coinciding with the growth in television, the [[Granada Television]] franchise was set up by [[Sidney Bernstein, Baron Bernstein|Sidney Bernstein]]. Consequently, the [[Granada Studios]] were the first purpose-built television studios in the United Kingdom. The franchise produced television programmes such as ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and the ''[[Up Series]]''. The [[BBC]] currently has two of its six major business divisions based here [[BBC North|BBC North Group]] that comprises a number of important departments including [[BBC Breakfast]], [[CBBC (TV channel)|BBC Children's]], [[BBC Sport]], [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]] and [[BBC North West]]. The other division is [[BBC Future Media]]. In addition [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] has two major divisions of its business based here [[ITV Studios]] responsible for UK and international network production and [[ITV Granada]] its regional service provider. The [[University of Salford]] also has a media campus and research center based at media city.<ref>{{cite web|last=UK Campus|first=Media City|title=Courses and Training|url=http://www.salford.ac.uk/mediacityuk|work=Research Center|publisher=University of Salford|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom is known for its large music industry, along with its new and upcoming artists. In the UK, media is spread through the forms of TV, newspapers, magazines, websites, and radio.\n\nThe ''Daily Mirror'' was founded in 1903.<ref>''[[Daily Mirror]]''</ref> The ''Sunday Mirror'', the sister paper to the ''Daily Mirror'', was started in 1915.<ref>''[[Sunday Mirror]]''</ref>\n\n===Other Key centres===\nEdinburgh and Glasgow, and Cardiff are important centres of newspaper and broadcasting production in Scotland and Wales respectively.<ref>D. William, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7yg45P35KDMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=William,+UK+Cities:+A+Look+at+Life+and+Major+Cities+in+England,+Scotland,+Wales+and+Northern+Ireland&hl=En&ei=Ej77TY2jG9Or8QPui8mqCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-thumbnail&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''UK Cities: A Look at Life and Major Cities in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland''] (Godfrey Mwakikagile, 2010), {{ISBN|9987-16-021-2}}, pp. 22, 46, 109 and 145.</ref>\n\nThe BBC, founded in 1922, is the United Kingdom's publicly funded radio, television and Internet broadcasting corporation, and is the oldest and largest broadcaster in the world. It operates numerous television and radio stations in the United Kingdom and abroad and its domestic services are funded by the [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|television licence]].<ref name=\"MediaNewsline\">{{Citation|last=Newswire7 |title=BBC: World's largest broadcaster & Most trusted media brand |journal=Media Newsline |date=13 August 2009 |url=http://www.medianewsline.com/news/151/ARTICLE/4930/2009-08-13.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510090842/http://www.medianewsline.com/news/151/ARTICLE/4930/2009-08-13.html |archivedate=10 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=TV Licence Fee: facts & figures |journal=BBC Press Office |date=April 2010 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/keyfacts/stories/licencefee.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427080539/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/keyfacts/stories/licencefee.shtml |archivedate=27 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref>\n\nOther major players in the United Kingdom media include [[ITV plc]], which operates 11 of the 15 regional television broadcasters that make up the ITV Network,<ref>{{Citation|title=Publications & Policies: The History of ITV |journal=ITV.com |url=http://www.itv.com/aboutitv/publications-policies/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411224117/http://www.itv.com/aboutitv/publications-policies/ |archivedate=11 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref> and [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]], which owns a number of national newspapers through [[News International]] such as the [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and \"[[broadsheet]]\" ''[[The Times]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Publishing |journal=News Corporation |url=http://www.newscorp.com/operations/publishing.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604100008/http://www.newscorp.com/operations/publishing.html |archivedate=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Direct Broadcast Satellite Television |journal=News Corporation |url=http://www.newscorp.com/operations/dbst.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604095622/http://www.newscorp.com/operations/dbst.html |archivedate=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref>\n\n==Print==\nThe United Kingdom print publishing sector, including books, server, directories and databases, journals, magazines and business media, newspapers and news agencies, has a combined turnover of around \u00a320 billion and employs around 167,000 people. The print media sector is entirely regulating itself and there are no specific statutory rules regulating the print media.<ref>{{Citation|title=Publishing |journal=Department of Culture, Media and Sport |url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/creative_industries/3280.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505104322/http://www.culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/creative_industries/3280.aspx |archivedate=5 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref>\n\n===Newspapers===\n{{Main|List of newspapers in the United Kingdom|History of British newspapers}}\nTraditionally British newspapers have been divided into \"quality\", serious-minded newspapers (usually referred to as \"[[broadsheet]]s\" because of their large size) and the more populist, \"[[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]]\" varieties. For convenience of reading many traditional broadsheets have switched to a more [[compact (newspaper)|compact]]-sized format, traditionally used by tabloids. In 2008 ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' had the highest circulation of any daily newspaper in the United Kingdom at 3.1&nbsp;million, approximately a quarter of the market.<ref name=paper>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/table/2008/oct/10/abcs-pressandpublishing |title=ABCs: National daily newspaper circulation September 2008 |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=17 October 2008 |date=10 October 2008}}</ref> Its sister paper, the ''[[News of the World]]'', had the highest circulation in the Sunday newspaper market,<ref name=paper/>  and traditionally focused on celebrity-led stories until its closure in 2011.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14096215 Phone-hacking probe: 'Thank you & goodbye', says NoW], ''BBC News'', 10 July 2011, retrieved 11 July 2011.</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', a centre-right broadsheet paper, is the highest-selling of the \"quality\" newspapers.<ref name=paper/> While ''[[The Guardian]]'' is a centre-left \"quality\" broadsheet and the ''[[Financial Times]]'' is the main business newspaper, printed on distinctive salmon-pink broadsheet paper.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/25/world/europe/25britain.html |title=British Panel Condemns Media Group in Phone Hacking Case |work=The New York Times |accessdate=30 December 2010 | date = 24 February 2010 | first = Sarah | last = Lyall}}</ref> In 2018 [[Reach plc]] (formerly Trinity Mirror), which operates 240 local and regional newspapers in the United Kingdom as well as the national newspapers ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' and ''[[The People]]'', purchased [[Northern & Shell]] which added the ''[[Daily Express]]'', ''[[Daily Express#Sunday Express|Sunday Express]],'' ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'' and three celebrity magazines to its stable.<ref>{{Citation|title=Trinity Mirror plc: Annual Report and Accounts 2010 |journal=Trinity Mirror |year=2010 |url=http://www.trinitymirror.com/pdf/annual_report_2010.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515221657/http://www.trinitymirror.com/pdf/annual_report_2010.pdf |archivedate=15 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}.</ref><ref name=pg-20180620>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/culture-secretary-gives-green-light-to-reach-takeover-of-express-newspapers/ |title=Culture Secretary gives green light to Reach takeover of Express Newspapers |last=Tobitt |first=Charlotte |work=Press Gazette |date=20 June 2018 |accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nScotland has a distinct tradition of newspaper readership (see [[list of newspapers in Scotland]]). The tabloid ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' has the highest circulation of any daily newspaper, outselling ''[[The Scottish Sun]]'' by four to one, while its sister paper the ''[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]'' similarly leads the Sunday newspaper market. The leading \"quality\" daily newspaper in Scotland is ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'', though it is the sister paper of ''[[The Scotsman]]'', and the ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'' that leads in the Sunday newspaper market.<ref>{{Citation|first=Chris |last=Tryhorn |title=Scottish Sun pulls further ahead of Record |journal=guardian.co.uk |date=9 May 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/09/abcs.pressandpublishing4 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316152457/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2008/may/09/abcs.pressandpublishing4 |archivedate=16 March 2009 |url-status=dead }}.</ref> In November 2014 a new newspaper was launched in Scotland called ''[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]''.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/nov/21/the-national-pro-independence-newspaper-launch-scotland Pro-independence daily paper the National to launch in Scotland]. The Guardian. Author - Mark Sweney. Published 21 November 2014. Retrieved 5 May 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 2018 [[TheGuardian.com]], [[News UK]] (''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'') and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' created a joint platform for advertisers to buy online adverts across the multiple leading news websites, called The Ozone Project.<ref name=guardian-20180620>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jun/20/guardian-news-uk-telegraph-launch-advertising-business-ozone-project |title=Guardian, News UK and Telegraph launch joint advertising business |last=Waterson |first=Jim |work=The Guardian |date=20 June 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref> Later in the year [[Reach plc]] joined the platform, bringing nearly all of UK's national newspapers onto the platform.<ref name=pg-20180911>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/joint-advertising-platform-becomes-truly-cross-industry-initiative-as-reach-unites-with-news-uk-guardian-and-telegraph/ |title=Joint advertising platform becomes 'truly cross-industry initiative' as Reach unites with News UK, Guardian and Telegraph |last=Tobitt |first=Charlotte |work=Press Gazette |date=11 September 2018 |accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, the newspaper with the highest circulation is [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] with 1,426,535 readers.<ref name=\"pressgazette.co.uk\">https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/national-newspaper-abc-daily-star-sunday-print-drop-first-2020-circulation-figures/</ref> [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] and other tabloid daily newspapers have seen a drop in circulation.<ref name=\"pressgazette.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Broadsheet and former broadsheet newspapers==\n\n:{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Title\n! Days of<br>publication\n!Circulation\n! Established\n!Editor\n! Owner\n! Political<br>orientation\n![[Endorsements in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|Political party support<br>in the 2019 general election]]\n! Format\n\n|-\n| ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' || Daily \n|308,015|| 1855\n|[[Chris Evans (journalist)|Chris Evans]]|| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Press Holdings]] ([[Barclay brothers]]) || rowspan=\"4\" |[[Centre-right]], [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]]|| rowspan=\"4\" |{{Nowrap|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Cons